author: @jimihen1112
processed_text: What is the best way to incorporate high dimensional categorical variables into a regression tree?

author: @JasonSanchezLogic
processed_text: Based on 1:18:20, it seems like replacing the categorical values with random numbers would works.Another possible solution is to replace each categorical value with the average of the response variable for that group. Because this strategy uses the response variable for data manipulation, you must do it within a CV scheme to get a fair generalized error rate. Concretely: For each CV fold, compute the average value of the response variable for each categorical value. Replace each categorical value with its respective mean. Train the algorithm and test on the excluded CV fold. Another possible solution is to dummy all the variables (One hot encoding), train a regularized linear model on the data, then replace the original categorical values with the beta terms of the trained linear model. All of this must be done inside of the context of CV. This slightly more advanced method helps adjust for correlations between variables.

author: @waltermcmain3461
processed_text: ...I always wondered if when you show a three year old a cat, if deep in their brain there isn't a group of neurons that immediately generates thousands of images based of the initial cat image, with small variations that keep the same form, and the brain assumes that these would also be cats...  And it would then give rise to the three year old later imagining cats doing non-cat related things, until they get more solid information on cats and their real descriptive attributes.Like the brain just stuffs cats into all kinds of different positions, dreams about cats doing things even if they've never seen the cat do those things, just so they can be that much more prepared for cats the next time they are encountered..At that point, I would imagine that familiarity with cats, even if simulated familiarity, is better than having only one experience to draw from... but since the simulated cats are imagined and do not reflect reality, we aren't consciously aware of those simulations, we just feel more familiarized with real cats than we actually are, and the brain is slowly replacing simulated knowledge and assumptions, with actual knowledge.

author: @waltermcmain3461
processed_text: So in that way, when we show a learning algorithm a bunch of images so it's familiar with something, we're not emulating full working learning, but rather one small aspect.  In theory I guess, that would mean you could make something more like a three year old, if you figured out how to take one image, modify it slightly and in different ways thousands of times, until the system can more accurately identify the things in that image, without actually seeing a different image of that object.

author: @waltermcmain3461
processed_text: Like a physics student making a free body diagram.  Iteration of the initial image can provide additional details or simplify the situation for more complex and precise information processing.

author: @bizlibrarian
processed_text: +paul martin Hi! Thank you for your feedback on my comment. I agree I am being hard on Google as far as snark goes, but not in terms of expectations. Speech recognition technology is only the first part of captioning to capture extemporaneous speaking. It was impressive how well the speech recognition worked with so much other potential noise in a large room and with the speaker walking around.  But, that said, transcripts need to be cleaned up to account for punctuation, misspellings or wrongly captured words. Captioning is not about the essence of what is said it is about relaying what is actually said, how it was said and it should include other sounds in the room, like laughter or other sounds in the environment that are part of the experience.I regularly caption my work videos using a combination ofCamtasia’s built in captioning tool which uses Microsoft’s speech recognition software that comes with the computer I use. After I lay down a narrated video, Camtasia will create time stamped captions which I then edit to clean up misheard words and to add punctuation. It then takes just a short amount of time to clean up the captions and it is very easy to export and upload to the captioned file to YouTube when I post videos there. I can make and post a captioned 5 minute video in which I speak off the top of my head in less than a half hour. In my situation the biggest barrier is the cost of Camtasia, around $300. A $25 headset with a microphone takes care of good audio and YouTube takes care of server space to post videos. I work for an employer that has no qualms with the time spent to do this and expects videos to be captioned cleanly and correctly.Because this particular video is about accessibility, because Google has the time, money and availability of labor to take these extra steps they should be called out. A small non-profit with limited financial and human resources could be excused for not adding captions, but then again to transcribe something by hand and then time stamp the captions in YouTube is very doable. It just takes time which most people choose not to take or they choose to use the imperfect speech recognition technology when a few extra steps could produce a more accessible end product. I do acknowledge that one big barrier is employers not giving employees the tools, resources and mandate to caption.Captions, and descriptive text for those who are visually challenged, should be provided universally. In the States this issue is getting litigated more and more as groups sue entities for not captioning. http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/13/education/harvard-and-mit-sued-over-failing-to-caption-online-courses.html?_r=0Maybe at some point YouTube will be the focus of one of these suits.Thanks again for adding to this conversation!

author: @vonkruel
processed_text: "Simulation isn't duplication".  True enough as a general statement, but if you simulate what the brain does, there's no way you haven't created an intelligence.  Obviously you can't feed a pizza slice to a program that simulates what the digestive system does, but that's a useless analogy here.  We don't even need to simulate everything going on in the brain -- just the key mechanisms that enable intelligence.  This is not duplicating a brain ; it's making another machine that performs the same  intelligence-enabling processes that manipulate information.  The reason it hasn't happened yet has nothing to do with inherent limitations of what we're able to do with hardware & software.  "All" we need is to understand the key processes in the brain that enable intelligence.  It's a great challenge to be sure, but some of the puzzle pieces have already been assembled.  Won't happen in the next decade?  Probably right.  Won't happen in the next 50 years?  Not so sure.

author: @adrct
processed_text: +Vasily Kuznetsov He doesn't believe that only biological systems are capable of consciousness. A machinery that could duplicate the way that a human brain works would be able to develop consciousness. Now, a Turing machine does not accomplish that (because its operations are purely syntatic, deprived of any semantic content), although it could simulate consciousness well enough to trick us into believing that it is conscious (that's basically the point of the the chinese room argument).

author: @entwine
processed_text: +adrct You seem to be on the same page with Searle, could you explain to me the difference between "syntax" and chemistry that makes consciousness built upon "syntax" impossible? I put "syntax" in quotes here because Searle seems to be bundling a lot of things into this term: physics, electronic circuits, binary data, programs, etc.

author: @adrct
processed_text: +Vasily Kuznetsov I wouldn't really say I am on the same exact page with Searle, and I am certainly not a specialist on any of the subjects implied in the debate. (I am a theoretical physicist working on gravitation, cosmology, and the like.). I just happen to have an interest because I think the theme is both fascinating and relevant.According to Searle one difference is that the brain can be affected by stimuli that are not equivalent to a computational input. He points out that the way cocaine acts on the brain is not dependent on the substance's computation capacity, but rather on how it affects the very neurobiological processes carried out in the brain. And cocaine, as we know, does have cognitive effects. (Maybe it would be more interesting to take hallucinogenic drugs as an example, since there is a claim that they can enhance criativity.) Now computers are a whole different story, since they are implementation-independent.

author: @entwine
processed_text: +adrct Agreed, the brain can be affected by stimuli that are not inputs. But so can the computer. For example if we increase the amount of memory or slow down the processor, it will affect the computation in come way. It's not quite the same as taking substances that alter the way neurons react to inputs, but if we're just interested in the possibility to be affected, it's enough. And if we need something more similar to hallucinogens or other drugs, we would likely find a way to simulate their effects.In any case, if one says that this ability of the brain to be affected by non-inputs is necessary for consciousness, this is a strong claim. I'm not sure why we would think that this is true.

author: @micahnelson4883
processed_text: Assuming I haven't misunderstood, to bring up examples of weak AI and say that computers aren't smart like humans, and then imply they never will be, is either myopic, disingenuous, or misleading.  I think the question posed by the gentleman at 53:00 was driving to a proper point, but could be better expressed with the following:Since all living things are made up by simpler components and almost all physical matter can be simulated in a virtual environment, why is it so hard to come to the conclusion that we can simulate a human brain?  To make the statement more concrete,  we can learn how the human brain works and simulate (with sufficient resources) each individual component of the human brain (like neurons(and their subcomponents), glials, etc), effectively making a virtualized human brain.  Thus, anything a human can do, this machine could do, but about a million times faster (including being empathetic in counterargument to his example) with almost perfect recall (there could be bits in errors outside of correction) and nearly infinite scalability.  Hence, singularity.  Moreover, with this technology, it would even be possible to clone a human's brain virtually. However, this does have some interesting implications as far as the cloned, virtual brain going crazy, since it has no real ability to "relieve" perceived biological desires, as well as other issues.I'll stop there.

author: @micahnelson4883
processed_text: +Michael Shull Yes, I agree, there is still much to learn.  However, my example is the rather brute force method of obtaining strong AI.  I believe there are simpler, less resource intensive models and I think Claus Emmeche succintly sums this up in "The Garden in the Machine:" "All life is form. Neither actual nor possible life is determined by the matter of which it is constructed. Life is a process, and it is the form of this process, not the matter, that is the essence of life. One can therefore ignore the material and instead abstract from it the logic that governs the process, taking it out of the concrete material form of the life we know. Hence, one can thus achieve the same logic in another material 'clothing' or substratum. Life is fundamentally independent of the medium." (pg. 18).Once we can formalize our brains' processes, we can most likely carve off a lot of superfluous function for a silicon substratum (like perhaps sleep/dreaming, for instance).In regards to us being in a simulation, have you ever heard of Roko's basilisk?  Even though it doesn't really hold up under scrutiny, it can yield some interesting thoughts...

author: @panpiper
processed_text: Creating a secular ethics is an extremely laudable goal. I fear however it fails if it requires, as was stipulated repeatedly here, that one accept the immortality of the self. Not having such a faith does not equate to nihilism. I have to wonder if this is not an attachment in Buddhism? I may not exist at a given point in time, but the universe does exist in all points of time.  The fact that I have suffered in this universe need not dissuade me from loving it for the happiness and beauty it also contains and has gifted me with.  I act to create a better world not for reasons of enlightened 'immortal' self interest but simply because I have sufficient love for the universe and that which exists within it. It is the immortality of the universe that I love, that is my motive, not the faith in my own. I am personally enriched now, in this life, by virtue of this love at the same time as I am able to enrich that which I love. Whether I am enlightened or attain enlightenment is relevant only as a guidepost, we need not be attached to enlightenment either.The assertion here that science cannot prove that nothingness exists, and that that 'proves' that nothingness does 'not' exist, is fallacious. That said, I am not convinced that one need have a 'faith' in one's personal immortality in order to 'be enlightened', one need not be so attached to one's self. Indeed, realizing that one may in fact have only one life is if anything to me, more impetus to get it right, right now. There may well not be time later.

True, value is subjective, but that is much different from saying these things have no value. author: @MmAWC333
processed_text: Great talk David.  It's quite sad that sometimes people with good intentions, like the guy at the end concerned about recording dying languages, take their frustrations out on completely benign artistic endeavors like conlanging.  It's sad because that attitude is basically implying that people who have a genuine love for language and want to engage artistically with it are doing something wrong because they aren't devoting their energy to getting out in the field.  It's a really bizarre argument.  David's analogy about the fiction writer and historian is a good one, and it threw the guy off.  He didn't explain why David's analogy was fallacious despite claiming it was, he just rebutted with a false analogy himself.  Choosing to devote your interest and skills in language to using language artistically is in no way equivalent to ISIS destroying cultural artifacts.  In the ISIS analogy, people are actively destroying cultural artifacts, not merely neglecting them because they're choosing to devote their energy to do art instead of artifact protection lol; what a strange argument.  And in David's case, he shouldn't be considered doing a disservice to dying languages because he's not himself out there recording languages.  Conlanging isn't done at the expense of language preservation.  To argue otherwise, you're basically saying that art of any form is a disservice to humanity because in a hypothetical world artists with any practical skills could be devoting their energy to other things.  I don't imagine many people would defend that perspective when it comes to traditional art forms, yet for some reason when it comes to people playing artistically with language in this manner (an art form just really starting to catch on) some people get all riled up.  The position is very illogical.  Furthermore, conlangs in art media seem to be getting a lot of people interested in language and linguistics who otherwise wouldn't have become interested in these things.  People getting excited about language, no matter how that initial excitement begins (through art or otherwise), seems to only be a good thing to me.

author: @mochako2
processed_text: +Matt R You don't need to be a woman in order to participate in the discussion. But you do need to be a woman, and in particular, one that faces issues of gender inequality, in order to comment on whether this is still "a moral cause". More importantly, to claim that this is an "over the top feminist agenda" and to suggest that Google silence the voice of Eileen Pollack, who is representing the many women that face these issues, can not be decided by someone who is not in that group.For example, if you are not black, you can not tell black people that racism doesn't exist and that they don't face issues of racial discrimination. If you are not gay, you can not tell homosexuals that they do not face issues of discrimination. If you are not transgender you can not tell transgender people that they also do not face discrimination. If you are not part of a particular group, it is irresponsible to claim that it isn't an issue any more because for the people within that group it is still a very real problem, whether you think so or not. So I stand by my initial question: "Are you a woman?". You are free to participate in the discussion, but how can you tell someone this isn't an issue any more when for that person it still is?Our job is to recognize that there are women who feel and live through this and rather than try to belittle this issue by saying this is an over the top feminist agenda, why not try to listen and support them. The fact that it is still being discussed AND being met with hostility is evidence that it is not resolved. It's true for women, and it's true for any group or individual that face discrimination.ps I am not a woman.

author: @mochako2
processed_text: +Matt R Listen and keep an open mind. You might surprise yourself to learn that people have vastly different experiences than your own; even if others can't minimize their lives to a few reasons that you think are valid or logical.

author: @mochako2
processed_text: +Matt R We do agree on some things. My intention with saying "listen" was exactly to point out that some people might talk about feminism in the context of your Tumblr example but as I alluded to in my original comment regarding women CEOs and scientists... I myself am a scientist and definitely experience first hand colleagues that are not paid equally, not given the same career opportunities, that are talked down to in meetings, that are not given the same opportunities for grants, etc,. When I think of gender inequality, I'm interested in addressing those kinds of issues. Sure some people may go on Tumblr and people can do and say whatever they want, but by listening to everyone with an open mind, it's easy to see that this is still a problem today on many important issues.The main thing is that I was not born a girl. I did not go to elementary school as a girl, high school as a girl, I did not go to university as a woman, nor grad school as woman. I have not worked as a woman and have no experiences as a woman. Therefore, even if a woman claims that she has been discriminated against because she is a woman, and I don't agree that what she says is discrimination, I have not experienced the billion memories this woman has that culminate her thinking this and this is my primary issue with people tell other people how to feel. I will never be able to understand what it is like to be a woman entirely, so the best I can do is listen and support the woman around me that I see are facing these issues. You don't have to support every "feminist" claim but in regards to this talk, Eileen Pollack is a scholar and a talented contributor to the New York Times. She isn't just some girl on Tumblr and is, in fact, raising many important points. You are free to support any issues you feel are important to you. I am trying to support my friends and colleagues.

author: @JuanRamirez-jh3ub
processed_text: The AR-15 was not just chosen for the weapon's lightness, but for the fact that a tiny little high velocity .22 caliber round could create such devastating soft target damage due to it's high kinetic energy. The wounds that they saw in tests on pigs ( the predecessor to ballistic gelatin) rivaled the larger and heavier rounds.  And now all soldiers could carry MANY more rounds on them than the heavier .30 caliber rounds in service at the time.  So much so that the Soviets abandoned their .30 caliber round (the 7.62x39 for the AK-47) in 1974 ( the 5.45x39)...and hence now use the AK-74 (for 1974) - an attempt to copy the round of the 5.56/.223 US round.  It was a study in particle physics...where a small object creates extensive "damage" as the velocity increases (if you double the mass of a "projectile" you double the kinetic energy...if you double the velocity....you QUADRUPLE the kinetic energy).

author: @JenniferArrow
processed_text: 35:49-37:25“We found also that this lifestyle saves a lot of money. When I embarked on this journey, my husband was a little worried. He said, you know I am starting this startup in the middle of a recession, we cannot afford to be going to the health-food store and the farmer’s market. And I encouraged him to compare our bank statements between our zero-waste lifestyle and our pre-zero-waste lifestyle. And he found that we were saving 40 percent on our overall spending. This is due to the fact that:“(1) We consume way, way, way less than we did before. Today we are no longer adding things to our inventory, we are only replacing what needs to be replaced: a sneaker that has a hole in it or a T-shirt that is too small. And when we buy the replacement, we buy it secondhand, which by definition is cheaper. “(2) We buy our food in bulk. One needs to know that when you buy a food in packaging, 15 percent of the price covers the packaging, so when you buy in bulk, you make an automatic 15 percent savings.“(3) And finally we’ve replaced anything that’s disposable in our house with a reusable alternative, so that means we are no longer investing our money in things that you throw away. We’re no longer investing our money in the landfill. We are no longer basically throwing our money out the window. We’ve invested our money in things we can use over time, reuse over time, and this has translated into huge cumulative savings. Actually, those savings have even allowed us to install solar on our home, which then allows us to save even more. The zero-waste lifestyle is the gift that keeps on giving.”

processed_text: +Angelika I would imagine that hearing impaired persons who use the closed captioning to experience this talk would care.I also noticed at 48:03 they transcribed "know that" but I believe she's saying "did an audit," which refers to a specific term in waste management, a "waste audit," cf http://www.nrdc.org/enterprise/greeningadvisor/wm-audits.asp

author: @AngelaPickles1929
processed_text: +Jennifer Arrow Close captioning is never accurate.  Never has been never will be.  I was really referring to Beth's definition of TARE.  Was giving the definition of TARE really necessary or does Beth think she is smarter than everyone else?

author: @petercobourg6578
processed_text: now if we could just get all non vegans of the world to see the pain and suffering they are causing. Animals are my friends. I don't eat my friends. The golden rule.

author: @MsGloaming
processed_text: +Josip Ivanić exactly. my sister once said to me when I ate some eggs and bacon, that my meal was a meal of animal suffering. I was like "no, it is just my delicious tasting meal, I am a nice person, what do you want from me crazy person?" No one eats meat because they do not respect or like animals. We eat it, because we disconnect the information. A key thought for me was "would I go eat outside now and kill one of the chickens/cows/rabbits because I would love the taste?" I mean I could feed myself without killing them, I would only do that if I absolutely had to. So I decided that as long as it is not neccesary, I would not harm animals (through my intentional behavior , so this means also in the restaurant/supermarket). This is a quite moral/ethical decision for me which does not involve fuzzy feelings of "all animals are my fluffy friends". I also make sure to never accuse anyone for eating meat, because I once did it myself and I am not a differnt person now. I just make different decisions.

author: @MsGloaming
processed_text: Animals also are cruel; the more intelligent they are, the crueler they can be. Dolphins are known to rape their mates, certain birds kill just for fun and some apes kill the babys of their rivals. Would you say that these things are OK for humans to do because animals do it too? Plus animals do not have the capacity to have moral/ethical considerations, therefore they can not be expected to act as if they did. Furthermore, in factory farming, we inflict suffering on animals that is completely unnecessary; animals do not keep other animaly in captivity where they suffer until they are killed; animals kill what they need to kill. Theodore M. K.

author: @petercobourg6578
processed_text: Theodore M. K. The great thing about being human is we can make a choice to eat animals or not eat them. Carnivores don't have a choice. They must eat them. Omnivores like bears have a choice as well but they just eat things that are plentiful and some of it is meat. I've made a moral connection that animals want to live just like I want to live. That way I can enjoy their beauty from a distance. It's becoming clear they possess the same traits as humans. They have a language, build homes, raise their young, they get happy, sad, mad, become afraid and they probably wonder about their future. So just as I won't eat my dog I decided to cut out 5 other animals as well (cow,pig,sheep,birds and fish). There are many other reasons like climate change, health etc. Also we get everything we need from plants. Animals eat plants to live we eat animals. I just cut out the middle man and go directly to the source of all my vitamins and nutrients and protein.

author: @kitarox22
processed_text: I would like to be able to go car free occasionally but I live 10-15 min from work by car and I have to be to work at 7:00 which is early for me so if I had to walk or bike it would take significantly longer and there isn't any good paths to get there. I have been to Boston twice because my sister was going to MIT and when visiting it was just normal to take the T(subway) to get around and a lot of walking which I found really cool because it's not like that where I live. However, I think when you look at the time saved by taking a car if it indeed does save a significant amount of time then I wouldn't even consider any other form of transportation because the more time I have the more time I can spend with family and friends or go out and have fun instead of spending my time commuting to and from work. I will also say that I live in a suburb near Minneapolis/St. Paul and when you live in a suburb it's extremely hard to get anywhere without a car because places are more spread out and farther apart. So for a big city going car free can be a reality but not really for those living in the suburbs and I wouldn't change that because the point for me of the suburbs or you could call it country living is the idea of more space, more land, smaller communities and a closeness among everyone. Public transportation in the suburbs would take away from the extra land, scenery, and essentially everything that makes living outside a city so appealing.

The best thing about this is that she really cares about it. She truly believes what she's saying and she can transmit that belief.Alternative Travel Project's had a huge effect on this subject around the Globe; I know this because I live in Uruguay and I am here, talking about it and moving around on my bike. I've seen fans around the world sharing their stories and experiences. That's amazing. This is making a change in the world. I've been crazy about the environment since I can remember but sadly, I can't do much about it; seeing people like her doing it makes me happy, makes me believe.

author: @oscarjensen9999
processed_text: In Denmark (like in Holland) a lot of people cycle to work and school. I personally have always cycled and taken the bus (in the winter) and a lot of my friends have done the same. In kindergarden the kids learns to cycle and in school we would cycle on classtrips and i remember when we were around 11 years we were tought in school how to cycle proberly in a more trafficated area (we even got a biking certificat). Now i live in the second largest city in Denmark (Aarhus, which i know is nothing compared to LA or a lot of other cities in the US) but here there is queue on the bike lane, because so many cycle, however it is still faster to cycle than to drive in your car. One of the things that i like is that there are separat traffic lights for cyclers which means that it is more safe and that the drivers are more aware of the people cycling. The bike lane is also many times divided into two (one for those who are going staright ahead and one for those who are turning right) which again makes it more safe. They have done something similar with busses where there are lanes only used by the busses, which again makes it easier and more safe. Further more there are boxes around the city that counts how many cyclists have passed it. It is funny to see that at 8 o'clock in the morning already around 600 cyclist has passed the the same box as you.    When you are cycling there are people handing you newspapers and during election you get folders about the different candidates, so i think that the shops could also benefit from having more cyclers because they can advertise that way. Personally i use my hour of cycling to and from school everyday to clear my head, get som fresh air and new energy to start doing homework when i get home. Sorry for the long comment, but i think this is important and i think that Aarhus is doing a great job, that maybe can inspire others.

author: @fmilan1
processed_text: Question: Is the hack on the Pathfinder a real set of instructions?

author: @biku_lh
processed_text: From what I remember, the instructions Mark received were just simple file navigating and text editing. We don't really know the purpose or contents of the file Mark was editing, and we don't know the actual data Mark edited in beyond what the NASA engineers explained in the book (that much was left out).In simple terms, all Mark was doing was the equivalent of clicking through folders to find a text file and then copy/pasting a text block into it. Of course, the rover's file systems could only be navigated and edited via command line.. and the text couldn't be copied so easily lolSo.. it is a real set of instructions, but only partly. The file he edited is probably fictitious, and the rest of the instructions (the actual, important bulk of the stuff) were left out of the book.

author: @fmilan1
processed_text: Yes, I understood the procedure. I'm a programmer myself and I hacked lots of games in the 90s, mainly to play them for free. So, the question should be divided in two: 1) Was the directory and file to hack real? 2) The bytes replaced were really real? From what I understood, he linked Pathfinder to the rover. Since Pathfinder was launched in 1997, and the USB standard was introduced in 1995ish, then lets assume the hack was to allow the Pathfinder to recognize the rover's terminal.

processed_text: Barry, thanks for articulating a healthy, positive approach to autism based on acceptance and understanding. Autism is here, it is not going away and it is far more prevalent than many of us realize. Not only that, but the population of people diagnosed with autism making the transition to adulthood is exploding. I hope that your book and your work offer us all some guidance to deal with this new immigration of people from the confines of pathology and into the working world.

author: @lafroing
processed_text: I completely agree that it is a good thing to "de-pathologize" autism, and that autism is not a tragedy by any means. But I think there is a danger of going too far in the other direction by using overly-sugar-coated language – replacing the word "obsessions" with "enthusiasms" for instance. There is a difference between repetitive behavior that is enriching and productive, and behavior that is distracting and counter-productive.As a parent of an autistic young adult I worry that, in the rightful interest of inclusiveness and politeness, we risk indulging unhealthy behaviors for fear offending anyone. Of course what is "healthy" or "unhealthy" is subjective but I think most people intuitively know the difference. For example, Dr. Prizant's interest in daily bike rides and rock-collecting seems like a healthy enthusiasm; but if he repeated his bike rides throughout the day to the detriment of his work or family it could be considered an unhealthy obsession. That distinction is important.In this climate of fear of offending anyone, a climate with phrases like "trigger warnings" and "micro-aggressions", I worry that we will water down discourse and – ironically, in the name of tolerance – become more intolerant and shy away from following the facts wherever they may lead us.

author: @barryprizant8470
processed_text: +lafroing Thank you. Your point is important and well-taken.  In my book, Uniquely Human, I have sections with titles such as "When Enthusiasms Cause Trouble", but it is hard to cover all bases in a short talk.  And for the record, as mentioned in the Google Talk and in my book, the term "enthusiasms" was coined by the late Clara Claiborne Park, the first parent to write a book ("The Siege") about raising a child with autism, later followed by "Exiting Nirvana".  Clara is arguably one of the most important figures in the parent advocacy movement in the history of autism. Her daughter, Jessy, now in her 50s, is an accomplished artist but also is significantly impacted by her autism. Clara and her husband, David, made the choice to be creative in "looking at the cup half-full" despite Jessy's challenges, leading to a meaningful and engaged life for Jessy to this day. With all due respect, I do not believe that using the term "enthusiasms" is sugar-coating, it is "reframing".  It is one way to attack the over-whelming negative stigma of autism in mainstream society, that in my opinion, is a major inhibiting factor to promoting understanding, acceptance and opportunity for people with autism and their families.

author: @barryprizant8470
processed_text: +lafroing Two additional points - 1) Many people with autism now also say "Don't talk about my obsessions, talk about my deep interests". I believe that Reference to "obsession" is a dead end street and an external judgement. Reference to "deep interest" is an attempt to understand the person's perspective and opens up possibilities, even if we need to create boundaries by helping a person understand "there's a time and a place" (another section in my book).  2) In my book, I also discuss the difference between true OCD behaviors that are debilitating and interfering, in contrast to deep interests and enthusiasms that are emotionally regulating and engaging. The pathologizing perspective in autism has led to a "stop that behavior" bias that results in devaluing the person's perspective, preventing the development of trusting relationships and ultimately damaging the self-esteem of people on the spectrum (as now reported by many adults whose interests were squelched).

author: @lafroing
processed_text: +Barry Prizant  Thank you so much for responding to my comment!That is a good term: "reframing". I didn't feel that you specifically were "sugar-coating". And I agree we need to go far in the opposite direction to counter-balance the negative hyperbole of people like RFK Jr. I'm certain that you, being in this field, are using the terms in their proper spirit; I just am always vigilant against euphemizing - by misinformed people - in the name of political correctness. But euphemism is the far lesser evil than stigmatization, for certain.Watching your talk, I was thinking "he probably goes deeper into this in his book than in this short talk" - exactly as you point out.Thanks again for responding and for bringing better understanding of autism to the general public.

author: @AtSwimTwoBricks
processed_text: I just read an Amazon review that did the math on some of the book's recipes. Apparently Chang's regular recipe for Fudgy Mascarpone Brownies contains 6 teaspoons of sugar while the "low sugar" version contains 6.4. The trick is that the "low sugar" version had the sugar already in its ingredients and so required fewer literal teaspoons of white table sugar to be manually added. I don't think my body cares about this creative accounting. The sugar is still there in the end.So I'm left wondering about the other recipes. How much of this "low sugar" talk is result of simply ignoring the sugar content in honey, molasses, juice, sweetened chocolate, etc.?

author: @2LegHumanist
processed_text: Good talk.  The SJW online bullying, rape-culture hysteria and other products of extreme third-wave feminism are polarising people on this issue.  Most people I talk to about this are either pushed to the side of believing there is no problem or the side that suggests that the industry is rife with woman-hating nerds.  The reality is that there are problems that women experience in the industry that are not experienced by men.Is it hostile to women?  I think it is hostile to men and women and that women are more likely to walk away from a hostile work environment than men.One might retort that if you can't handle it you have no place being there.  But the industry has a general recruiting problem.  There is a global skills shortage that could be addressed by encouraging women into the industry and encouraging them to stay.It isn't just an argument about whether we should be more accommodating just to give the women-folk a leg up. There are clear economic reasons to want to encourage underrepresented demographics into the industry.Post Edit: I also want to point out a point on which the speaker differs considerably to the SJW brigade on this issue.  The SJWs insist that men and women are identical.  Acknowledging that we are not is the first step towards creating a work culture that is sensitive to the needs of women.

author: @ruzzellcrowe7166
processed_text: The truth is that we don't have the language to create the pictures of understanding about what's happening within Nature. Physics found this out over a hundred years ago with the double-slit experiment. We can model atoms to a certain degree and use those analogies and metaphors to explain the workings of an atom, but, it's only useful to a certain degree. Is an atom a wave or a particle? It's a question that will never be answered, because, we don't have the language to create the pictures to understand Nature. "I don't exist" is hard to understand when someone believes they do exist. People still question what is the I they are referring too. It's a descriptive word used to translate ourselves using understandings we've developed through our own growth path. I doesn't really exist is the sense that you're made up of billions and billions of individual cells, working in symbiosis to create the illusion of one entity. But, the entity isn't an illusion. It actually exists, but that someone just may be not making the same connections as the person who assumes the entity exists. People like to ask for the existence of God. Show me proof! Well, proof is in the thought of the believer. Thoughts are measurable and radiate outside of the human head. We can hook people up to computers and have them think of a tree or a circle and the computer can show what that person is thinking about - to a certain degree. Well, perhaps, eventually we're going to be able to see the idea of what God is to a person. God is simply a descriptive word with several different meanings to each and every person. Does God exists? Yep, but that doesn't mean that the same God inside your head exists for everyone. Natures' imagination is far more greater than our imagination. We believe we have the model correct with mathematics though, because our theories work. Now, all the new sciences are hitting the same wall that physics did a 100 years ago. The beauty of Nature.

author: @WraithsPassage
processed_text: While I really like and agree with what Carol Dweck says I feel she sidestepped the question around raw talent.  While everyone can improve their abilities, it is also true that our upper limits on growth in various areas are limited by factors that are not in our control.  Being able to recognize that is important.  Not everyone can be a professional basket ball player if they just try hard enough.  Same goes for being like Einstein.  Not everyone could have come up with the theory of relativity if they just tried hard enough.  Being able to recognize this is important because as a person gets better and better in a specialized area, the gains become smaller and smaller.  It can become more advantageous to the individual and society for that individual branch out and improve on other areas in comparison to focusing on a single skill in an effort to achieve something that might be literally beyond his or her capability.On a personal level I experienced this somewhat in my education but also in computer gaming.  Computer gaming is easier to explain so I will do so here.  It is a well know fact that somewhere in your late teens and early twenties your reaction speed is at it's peek performance.  I'm past my prime by a good 10 years.  There is no possible way, with any amount of training or dedication that I could ever beat someone in there prime in a video game that's almost exclusively based on reaction time.  It would be a waste of my time to try to become the best video game player at the expense of all the other skills I could be improving.

author: @lindamathews1745
processed_text: What Does the Bible Say About Homosexuality?PlayPauseDisable audioEnable audioDownloadMP3The Bible’s answerGod created humans to engage in sex only within the arrangement of marriage between a male and a female. (Genesis 1:27, 28; Leviticus 18:22; Proverbs 5:18, 19) The Bible condemns sexual activity that is not between a husband and wife, whether it is homosexual or heterosexual conduct. (1 Corinthians 6:18) This includes intercourse, fondling another person’s genitals, and engaging in oral or anal sex.While the Bible disapproves of homosexual acts, it does not condone hatred of homosexuals or homophobia. Instead, Christians are directed to “respect everyone.”—1 Peter 2:17, Good News Translation.Can a person be born homosexual?The Bible doesn’t comment directly on the biology of homosexual desires, though it acknowledges that we are all born with a tendency to go against what God commands. (Romans 7:21-25) Rather than focus on the cause of homosexual desires, however, the Bible prohibits homosexual acts.How to please God despite having same-sex urges.The Bible says: “Don’t be controlled by your body. Kill every desire for the wrong kind of sex.” (Colossians 3:5, Contemporary English Version) To kill wrong desires, which lead to wrong actions, you need to control your thinking. If you regularly fill your mind with wholesome thoughts, you can more readily dismiss wrong desires. (Philippians 4:8; James 1:14, 15) While you may struggle greatly at first, it can become easier. God promises to help you to “be made new in the force actuating your mind.”—Ephesians 4:22-24.The same struggle is faced by millions with heterosexual desires who wish to conform to the Bible’s standards. For example, those who are single with little prospect of marriage or who are married to a partner who is unable to function sexually choose to control their sexual urges despite any temptations they might face. They are able to live happily, and those with same-sex urges can do so as well if they truly want to please God.—Deuteronomy 30:19.

author: @lindamathews1745
processed_text: +Tina Koehler Some people praise such ones for their courage; others condemn them for their debauchery. Between the two extremes, many view homosexuality as nothing more than an alternative lifestyle. “When I was in school,” says Daniel, 21, “even straight kids felt that if you had a problem with the idea of homosexuality, you were prejudiced and judgmental.” *Attitudes about homosexuality may differ from one generation to another or from one land to another. But Christians aren’t “carried hither and thither by every wind of teaching.” (Ephesians 4:14) Instead, they adhere to the Bible’s view.What is the Bible’s view of homosexuality? If you live by the Bible’s moral code, how can you respond to those who label you prejudiced, judgmental, or even homophobic? Consider the following questions and possible responses.What does the Bible say about homosexuality?The Bible makes it clear that God designed sex to be engaged in only between a male and a female and only within the arrangement of marriage. (Genesis 1:27, 28; Leviticus 18:22; Proverbs 5:18, 19) When the Bible condemns fornication, it is referring to both homosexual andheterosexual conduct. *—Galatians 5:19-21.

author: @lindamathews1745
processed_text: +Tina Koehler Shouldn’t Christians treat all people with respect, regardless of their sexual orientation?Absolutely. The Bible says: “Honor men of all sorts” or, as Today’s English Version renders it, “Respect everyone.” (1 Peter 2:17) Therefore, Christians are not homophobic. They show kindness to all people, including those who are gay.—Matthew 7:12.I also choose not to smoke. In fact, I find the very idea of it repugnant. But suppose you’re a smoker and you feel differently. I wouldn’t be prejudiced against you for your view, just as I’m sure you wouldn’t be prejudiced against me for my view—am I right? The same principle applies to our differing views of homosexuality.”Didn’t Jesus preach tolerance? If so, shouldn’t Christians take a permissive view of homosexuality?Jesus didn’t encourage his followers to accept any and all lifestyles. Rather, he taught that the way to salvation is open to “everyoneexercising faith in him.” (John 3:16) Exercising faith in Jesus includes conforming to God’s moral code, which forbids certain types of conduct—including homosexuality.—Romans 1:26, 27.When it comes to popular opinion, Christians have the courage to walk against the crowdIf someone says: “Homosexuals can’t change their orientation; they’re born that way.”You might reply: “The Bible doesn’t comment on the biology of homosexuals, although it acknowledges that some traits are deeply ingrained. (2 Corinthians 10:4, 5) Even if some are oriented toward the same sex, the Bible tells Christians to shun homosexual acts.”✔ Suggestion: Rather than get ensnared in a debate about the cause of homosexual desires, emphasize that the Bible prohibits homosexualconduct. To make a comparison, you could say: “You know, many claim that violent behavior can have a genetic root and that as a result, some people are predisposed to it. (Proverbs 29:22) What if that was true? As you might know, the Bible condemns fits of anger. (Psalm 37:8;Ephesians 4:31) Is that standard unfair just because some may be inclined toward violence?”WHAT ABOUT BISEXUALITY?Although it can be found among both genders, it seems that bisexuality is becoming increasingly common in girls. Consider a few reasons.Attention“Boys openly admit that they think lesbians are appealing. Girls who lack self-confidence will do almost anything to make a guy like them.”—Jessica, 16.Curiosity“When you put something out there in movies, TV, and music that promotes girls kissing girls, teens will be tempted to try it—especially when they do not consider it to be wrong.”—Lisa, 26.Attraction“I met two bisexual girls at a party, and later I found out from a friend that they liked me. Eventually I started texting one of the girls, and I started developing feelings for her.”—Vicky, 13.If you want to please God, you should avoid experimenting with conduct that the Bible describes as unclean. (Ephesians 4:19;5:11) But what if you’re really drawn to both sexes? Many would urge you simply to embrace your sexuality and come out as bisexual. However, you should be aware that same-sex attractionis often nothing more than a passing phase. That’s what Lisette, 16, found. She says: “Talking to my parents about my feelings made me feel better. Also, through my biology classes in school, I learned that during the adolescent years, hormone levels can fluctuate greatly. I truly think that if more youths knew more about their bodies, they would understand that same-sex attraction can be temporary and they wouldn’t feel the pressure to be gay.”Even if your feelings are more deep-rooted than a short-lived growing pain, realize that the Bible presents you with a reachable goal: You can choose not to act on any wrong desires. *How could God tell someone who is attracted to the same sex to shun homosexuality? That sounds cruel.Such reasoning is based on the flawed notion that humans must act on their sexual impulses. The Bible dignifies humans by assuring them that they can choose not to act on their improper sexual urges if they truly want to.—Colossians 3:5.If someone says: “Even if you’re not gay, you should change your view of homosexuality.”You might reply: “Suppose I didn’t approve of gambling but you did. Would it be reasonable for you to insist that I change my view,  simply because millions of people choose to gamble?”✔ Remember this: Most people (including homosexuals) have some ethical code that causes them to deplore certain things—perhaps fraud, injustice, or war. The Bible prohibits those behaviors; it also draws the line at certain types of sexual conduct, including homosexuality.—1 Corinthians 6:9-11.The Bible is not unreasonable nor does it promote prejudice. It simply directs those with same-sex urges to do the same thing that is required of those with an opposite-sex attraction—to “flee from fornication.”—1 Corinthians 6:18.The fact is, millions of heterosexuals who wish to conform to the Bible’s standards employ self-control despite any temptations they might face. Their numbers include many who are single with little prospect of marriage and many who are married to a disabled partner who is unable to function sexually. They are able to live happily without fulfilling their sexual urges. Those with homosexual inclinations can do the same if they truly want to please God.—Deuteronomy 30:19.jw.org

He also confessed to it, repented of it, was taken to the police to be charged for it, and has not done it since. If Josh was still a pedophile today, then he should be judged and condemned.  Since he is not, but is forgiven, yes, as Christians we forgive him to.  That's what we do.  We do not encourage his sin, we do not make light of his sin, but we do forgive him.I do not know all of the Graham story, but no one in the church community condones adultary. Is homosexuality biblically acceptable?  The Bible's answer is no, therfore, my answer is no.  Let's just say for the sake of argument David and Jonathan had an inappropriate affection for each other.  They were both under the Law of Moses, they both knew the Law of Moses, and they honored it more than their affection for each other.  They therefore viewed God and His law more highly than themselves.  I however do not believe that is what the text is showing because of how negatively the rest of the Bible talks about homosexuality.  Even Matthew Vines says that the Bible talks of homosexuality in a negative light. author: @aft5748
processed_text: Mr. Vector Hi, I just watched this video and saw your comment. Maybe you can get a female podocarpus to soak up all that cytotoxic pollen that your neighbor's tree is producing? Podocarpus is used to make a chemotherapy drug for leukemia, and all parts of the plant are cytotoxic -- including the pollen -- meaning you are likely getting the side effects of chemotherapy treatment from breathing in all that podocarpus pollen (see Wikipedia).A lot of people I know nowadays seem to be getting allergies without the sneezing or itching eyes -- they just feel tired or fatigued all the time, or like they have a cold or flu for weeks at a time, that they keep catching over and over again during the year as different trees bloom and put tidal waves of pollen into the air.

processed_text: Gobekli and  Catalhoyuk are nothing more than ancient fighting stadium systems. Yet the hunter was from say Portland and got lost from his buddies and sadly no one found him. Except for some alcohol, lol. Even modern Eskimos do not rely sole on hunting and gathering anymore. They still do it to honor their past but they don't need to.Our ancestors who had the time to carve vast arrays of megalithic stone arrays have absolutely no time to individually hunt. They hunted in droves. This guy is British with a thousand piece of credentials, has he ever gone to a soccer\football game? We're still the same. Rituals, worshipping fake things (football teams), competing with others, especially  in other regions in peace or in war. It's what we have done for millions of years. processed_text: I have another theory that may explain the origins of society. Perhaps the thing that FIRST singled out hominids from other species (perhaps as far back as Australopithecus) - before even fire or tools - was our collective fear of the unknown: i.e. 'religious' superstition and the desire for us not to be free, but instead transfer responsibility for our future to 'spirit guides' or gods. That would explain many things, including grouping (or self-herding). That in turn would lead more naturally to a division of labour: various task groups. And that in turn would lead to having more time to pursue other 'passtimes'. It would also explain how a heirarchy based on joint 'faith' would grow readily, and how it is fundamentally hard to dismiss, for most, despite overwhelming evidence to the contrary, and seems to be ingrained into our primitive minds even until today.

author: @Madsy9
processed_text: Thomas McCabe You can "hack" the blockchain if you control over half of the network which validates the transactions. One might brush off such an attack as unfeasible or unlikely, but it is a potential attack vector and the probability of it being abused grows every day. Some of the largest miner groups have controlled such a large portion of the transactions at peak times by accident. Fortunately for everyone they had no nefarious intentions. There is also the issue that bitcoins are finite in quantity and that bitcoins are literally lost when people forget the password to their wallets or the wallet is lost. While bitcoins can be split up into really small fractions to mitigate this somewhat, this phenomenon might end up making a few individuals very rich, or bitcoins essentially worthless over time.Also to answer your other point, even when you do transactions with companies and people you trust, disagreements and disputes do occur. It doesn't necessarily mean that either party is deliberately trying to fraud the other. There are advantages of having chargebacks just like there are good arguments for a non-regulated currency system.Like all currencies, Bitcoin has some advantages and some disadvantages. If people want Bitcoin to become more popular and easier to use, we should at least be honest about the possible challenges with the system.

author: @CaesarInVa
processed_text: Great video.  Thank you for posting.  I have one quick question that perhaps you could answer for me.  According to some documentaries I've seen, it seems that on May 6th, the day before her loss, the Lusitania received two radio warnings, one from the British admiralty and the other from the ship's owners, indicating submarine activity in the vicinity of The Head of Kinsale and Fastnet Rock. Both of these locations were in the area through which Lusitania would have to sail the next day in its transit to Liverpool.  In response to the warnings, Captain Tuner set extra lookouts on the night of the 6th, darkened ship at sundown and closed all water-tight doors below the ship's waterline.  According to one documentary, the Lusitania's loss is attributable to flooding throughout the ship, but if Captain Turner set a condition of watertight compartmentalization on the evening before the torpedo attack, how did water spread from the torpedoed compartment to the others???  Did he order the watertight doors opened at daybreak?  I'm curious.  Usually, as a matter of precaution, ships close all watertight doors below the waterline (known in the Navy as Material Condition X-Ray)when they are entering or departing confined areas, such as shipping channels, ports and harbors, as a precautionary measure in the event of collision with another vessel.  I would have thought, given the Lusitania's proximity to St. George's Channel (which is the southern entry to the Irish Sea) at the time of her sinking, that Captain Turner would have at the very least set a state of minimal watertight compartmentalization as they neared the channel, even in the absence of the submarine warnings.

author: @publicme
processed_text: I'd like to suggest a major flaw in Singer's reasoning: It can fail to ever effectively resolve the problem we face with global poverty. It's a drop in the bucket compared to what that richest individuals in the world could do. But we prefer to let them go on creating poverty by not paying people enough in wages and instead hording it all for themselves. So, our energies would be better spent focused on the root challenge: Getting all of the super wealthy under the control of the masses, make them give more, make them pay better wages, etc etc. So, yeah, the big problem with Singer's approach is that it's like charity... it might alleviate some pain and suffering while allowing the core problem to persist. Root out greediness by the richest class and work down from there.

author: @zacboller8334
processed_text: It's interesting commenters are giving Garland grief.  I think he was extremely poised and articulate.  The moderator, on the other hand, while enthusiastic seemed insufficiently prepared for the interview.  Not that her questions were bad, they were quite good, but they were hardly crisp or concise.  I found her constant laughter at her own comments and extemporaneous ramblings a bit tiresome, as I suspect did Garland.  An interview is not the venue by which the interviewer shares his thoughts, no one cares.  It's about the person being interviewed.  Despite that it was a very interesting discussion about one of the finest sci-fi films of the past ten years.

He remains engaged, but because he can't really hide the fact that he's not happy to be there he comes across as a little rude. author: @BobbbyJoeKlop
processed_text: I think the point of view Gernot Wagner articulates that is of thee utmost importance is the fact that we really don't have a full understanding of the consequences of anthropogenic climate change. What is under way has never happened in the 4.5 billion year history of this planet in terms of the scale and rapidity of the CO2 being released into the atmosphere. There is no precedent. This makes all predictions much more speculative and likely to underestimate the risks. Science in general is a conservative practice in that reputations and credibility can be destroyed by making wild claims so there is a bias towards understatement. This is why I believe we are seeing the natural world change much faster than most predictions forecast. In many regards, science as a whole is now having to catch up with changes in the world and explain events after they happen rather than being ahead of them. The California drought is a good example of this. Although changes were predicted in the jet stream over a decade ago due to arctic warming by a small team working out of UC Santa Cruz, this prediction wasn't widely embraced by the scientific community. Yet, here we are.One of the most overlooked aspects of the issue I believe is how the Earth's crust is going to react to the warming of the atmosphere and oceans. While a lot of study and effort has gone into understanding how the latter may change not many resources have been spent on looking at what will happen to the lithosphere. It is unlikely that there won't be some amount of thermal expansion of the crust due to heat conduction coming from the atmosphere and oceans. It's difficult to imagine a greater threat to civilization other than dramatic changes in the crust which induce severe volcanic activity on scales into the millions of years as happened during the permian mass extinction event. In fact many now believe that the dinosaurs may have been killed off by prolonged volcanic activity out of India, in combination with an asteroid impact at the time. Also, there is the Toba event which nearly extinguished our species. Although it's difficult to say that this will or won't happen as this issue hasn't been part of any major study to my knowledge. Which is genuinely shocking given the calamitous dangers it presents. This is one of the greatest unknowns right now I believe. Just how will the crust react to the rapid heating? I don't think anybody really knows as this has never happened before in terms of geological speed, and no one seems to really even be looking at the issue with any serious funding.I believe the state of California should be putting more resources into looking at how the current drought and increased heat is effecting the major fault zones that run through this state and preparing for something beyond the worst case scenario earthquake forecast. It's already been found that the Sierra Nevada has risen several inches due to the lack of snow and ice. If these events are taken into account with recent studies that link the advancement and recession of water across fault zones in triggering quakes, as has been found in the Coachella Valley, the most severe consequence of the drought might not be the lack of water, but a massive tectonic shift in the crust due to heating and drying conditions. As scary as it might be for some, we need to get a grip on the fact that we are looking at systemic changes where reductionism can hamper our broader understanding of what is happening. It isn't just the air, oceans, and coastlines that are going to change.

author: @DustinRodriguez1_0
processed_text: As the NSA has tried to deceive the public about their capabilities and actions in response to some truth coming out, I took notice of the fact that they exploited the publics wrongheadedness about analysis which Bruce mentions in this talk.  If you read through what they have said, they consistently speak ONLY about human analysts viewing the fulltext of communications. Now, a few years earlier, there were other whistleblowers from the NSA.  I forget his name, but it should be easy to find.  One of the claims that he made was not so much about what the NSA does, but about why they believe their actions are legal.  He claimed that they had a legal defense for their actions which they kept very quiet, because they knew that it was very uncertain and they were uncertain that it would be able to survive a court challenge.  The way they have responded to current inquiries certainly lends a great deal of credibility to his claims.Their legal defense, which they hope to never have to actually speak in court because if it is defeated their actions would be severely undermined is this:  Communications do not legally qualify as "intercepted" until a human being reads (or listens to, etc) the fulltext of the communications.  They believe that this means they can capture, store, and, most importantly, analyze, summarize, classify, and even act on these communications and at no point are the communications 'intercepted' by their definition.  That should scare the hell out of people.  Pouring personal data into algorithms that will analyze it is far more dangerous than any human being reading the communications.  They can classify you are a 'potential threat' without a human ever reading a word of what you've said.  If your speech or actions are simply odd, you will be targetted.

author: @DustinRodriguez1_0
processed_text: I think Mr. Zak might be operating from a flawed premise in his work with companies and management.  He is promoting some ideas that management and companies LOVE (you don't have to give your employees any more money, they actually want something else - you'll find that in the first chapter of every management book), but he seems to be presuming that companies want to improve productivity.  It may seem like common sense that they would, but common sense is often misleading. If you look at the numbers, it quickly becomes clear that companies have no interest in improving productivity, or at least that goal is very low on their list of priorities.  For instance, there have been literally HUNDREDS of studies showing that open office plans are extremely destructive to productivity.  Yet, open plan offices are pretty much universal.  Similarly, studies have shown that people working from home are markedly more productive than people working in offices, yet companies with a remote-first stance are rarer than hen's teeth.Presenting objective evidence of ways to improve productivity is certainly worth doing... but companies are not going to listen.  They are not going to change their practices.  Technology has made employees so productive, and increases productivity at such rates year after year that most companies actually deal with problems of taking advantage of productivity.  Many software developers, for instance, either spend most of their time idle or, more commonly, mired in corporate processes designed only to fill time but which produce nothing of value.  I think (but I'm not sure) that the pain point here is that the corporate structure itself has been losing value since 1980 while its overhead costs have remained constant.  Employees get more productive, but the value of the things companies provide, both to the employee and to society, have either been abandoned or have been eliminated by technology.  The time is soon going to come when people realize that we simply don't need companies any longer - at least not structured in the way they are now.  Paying for an office, for multiple layers of management doing jobs which could be better done by software, in the face of the Internet making aggregating workers together in a shared space not just worthless but actually destructive of value... and on top of that they have abandoned pensions, abandoned salary increases that can keep an employee relevant while remaining at the same employer for more than 5 years, etc... companies are going to have to change radically to survive the upcoming assault of people working from home, coordinated with software and the Internet, with 90% less overhead than companies incur.

author: @amaam89
processed_text: For anyone who does not want to sit through the whole thing, but would like to know the basics of the method, you have 2 options.1--watch up to 21:18.2--Read my summary:There are 4 basic steps to the KonMari method of organizing.1) Tidy in One Shot. Work as quickly and completely as possible.2) Sort by Category NOT by location3) Selection Criterion is "Does this item spark joy?" If the answer is not an immediate "yes" then toss it.4) The (Optimal) Order of Purging is...a clothes, b books, c documents, d misc. items, and e mementos.Purging and organizing in this order helps train the individual how to best recognize the feeling of joy.

author: @juchikawa8467
processed_text: Here is my translation from the Q&A at 26:00 (It is not a literal translation, but I tried to grasp what Marie Kondo was trying to convey).  Q: "I have a lot of things that I need, but I don't like or they don't inspire joy.  How do I find the balance between keeping versus discarding them?" (Ex: GMAT book, old kitchen utensils).  A: "For the items that don't spark joy but are items that are necessities/essentials currently- Try to think of it in this way- as they are items that are BEING OF USE to you or supporting you.  This can also be thought of as: that they are items that are trying to make you happy or bring you joy.  So my advice is, if you are going to keep that item, then be PROUD of that item.  Then, to that particular item- shower it with many compliments.   You will then soon begin to harbor/sparkle joy with those items."    I'd like to take a moment to say thank you to the translator.  This little portion took me about 30min to translate trying to really think what Marie Kondo was trying to convey from her heart.  However, if I was on the spot like that- I would've probably only been able to make a literal translation.  The translator did a great job keeping Marie's words authentic- and she did not add her own opinions/emotions into the translation.  If translation was lost- it was most likely due to the overwhelming amount of amazingness Ms. Kondo had in each selected message she had for the audience.  This 42minute clip is only just the beginning of her magic!  The rest is truly only in her book.  If I can help in anyway to translate any other portion- please feel free to let me know! :D

What brings  you joy 2. how important it is to know HOW TO FOLD (because that is the building block to organizing) 3. what kind of life do you imagine/want it to be? author: @glennpowell1838
processed_text: How To Organize - Konmari Method1. Tidy in one shot as quickly and completely as possible. We need a shock to get it done. Therefore set a deadline for organizing. It could be one week if doing it everyday , every weekend, etc.. TIdying is not an every day event but think of it as a Festival, a special event2. How are you going to do it ? Sort by category, not by location. It never ends if you try to ticy in one portion of the closet or living room. Organize my category and do it quickly eg. If organizing the clothes first, make a big pile of all the clothes in your house . Similarly, take out all the books from your bookcase and organize then in one location in the house. When you bring out all your stuff in one location you can visually see how many books etc...that you have. We rarely understand how much stuff we have around us. It is a great opportunity to decide which ones you really need to keep or get rid of.The criteria for sorting what you need from what you don't is :3. Does it Spark Joy ?  If you look at one thing, you should question if that thing makes you happy, impressed. It's more important to think which one you want to keep than what to get rid of.How to make a decision :1. Make sure you touch the item.  Imagine how you feel when you touch it2.  You should feel a reaction from your body. If every part of your body is enlivened that is the right reaction3. If the item doesnt give you any inspiration, and your body starts feeling down...then you don't need it. Try this.. 17.26 ( to be continued )

author: @tracegates8841
processed_text: masterof101010 Hi masterof...  When I was applying the "spark joy" method, I was not necessarily getting joyous inspiration, per say, from the items.  What I was thinking of and feeling were the memories and/or hopes for the future that I thought of or felt with each item.  When I held an item, I thought of where I was in my life when I acquired it, was I at a happy place in my life, does it give me a happy memory, or am I remembering something unpleasant when I see, touch, or use this item.  Case in point, I had some items that I acquired during a previous relationship that only made me remember that person I did not like, who treated me unfairly, and no matter how useful the item had been to me, I could never use that item without remembering things I would rather not remember.  Those items were placed in donation.  I also touched items that brought back memories of fun summers at Grandma's house, or a happy trip to the beach, or a pleasant weekday shopping excursion to the city.  Those items are fun to have in my house, and they "spark joy" for me (for lack of a better term).

author: @stevenmonash624
processed_text: She debunks the myth that people are just born smart or there is some magic method of attaining success. What she is saying is not new. It is known by anyone who has gone through extensive study.. granted not all. For instance, basic strategies.. chunking ... practicing.. spacing learning... and finding comparative areas to complement existing knowledge and personalising.The trouble is people look for the short way of learning.. and it ends up being the long way. The long way is the short way in the long term. So, study hard and long and space and chunk.. be organised... and focus... remember study smart to be smarter. In order to focus have an approach to learning... be organised... try to understand rather than trying to remember....be a busy learner in class before and after. Yes, an eclectic range of methods not esoteric but in a way that will allow you to feel satisfied about what you are learning. Notice, I did not say what you have learnt. Nothing is for free you have to work for it. Common sense and simplicity to learn complex things. The guy or girl that turns up and gets the best grades has worked for it .. but worked in a smart manner... that best utilises time and leads to a deeper understanding that then becomes easy to remember. What we see we forget.. what we hear we remember what we do we understand. Forget the boring and childish games of well typically the female gender who socialise more than males... (double edge sword here) who claim they have done no study and just magically attain good grades.. There are many variables to getting good marks... people do not all start on the same start line.. For instance, I learned a second language not knowing one word of it... whereas, other students were false beginners and of course they appeared to be smarter, when in fact they had background. Smart students start courses early... a sense of urgency to map out a learning strategy.. they are organised... and want to create a learning environment for themselves. It is like sport .. you have to practice, warm up... build fitness, have and maintain good equipment... and hang out with more experienced people (judiciously) that is eventually you have to take some time out... to study alone. So, don't play those psycho semantic games with those who claim to be gifted.. they are very few and even they have to work bloody hard.. just not has hard as those who do not know and therefore, do not study smart... Success requires one to be selfish.. and judiciously share their time with others. And yes, just because you are eating from one paddock does not mean you can not go into the other paddock occasionally, the grass always looks greener, so value what you do.. but don't close yourself off to other disciplines. For instance, when I was studying linguistics... I found psychology had something to say on the subject... as well as politics ... anthropology and pretty much all disciplines. So cross disciplinary learning is a great way to find chunks from other fields. I hope this has helped somebody or many... having been selfish it is now time to share... Thanks.

author: @prwexler
processed_text: In this video, Bill Nye repeatedly raises the need for better energy storage and more efficient desalination systems.  I don't understand.  In SoCal, the answer to his challenge is this: solar cells in the deserts and windmills in the mountain passes with wires leading to the shore and connected at the terminal to an electrolysis system.The electricity produced by the windmills and solar cells should be used to electrolyze shoreline seawater. The hydrogen from the electrolysis should then be stored and used as necessary to run a turbojet driven dynamo.  The exhaust from the turbine engine is nothing but pure DESALINATED water.Wind and sun are the energy source.  Hydrogen is the "battery."  Hydrogen can be stored in vast tanks.  The tanks can be filled with nitrogen which would be displaced by hydrogen during the "charging" cycle, and the displaced nitrogen would flow into displacement tanks.Water electrolysis is not a cheap way to produce desalinated water, except when the electrolytic process is used to produce potential energy in the form of hydrogen gas which can then be run through a turbojet engine to spin dynamos at times when renewable power sources are unavailable, like at night or when there is no wind.I am not an original thinker.  Ten thousand people must be thinking the same thing as me.  So, why the ffuucckk is nobody doing anything like this?  Who are the nay-sayers standing in the way?  I know they're out there.

author: @shadfurman
processed_text: I started programming in basic at age 6,  completely self taught, I don't think programming is difficult for young kids, I think it's difficult for parents and teachers and for those parents and teachers to imagine kids can do something they don't understand, or didn't understand till they were older but still found difficult. I wasn't programming games at age 6, my first program was text that would scroll repeatedly in a kind of hypnotic pattern. I didn't make my first game till I was 13, not for lack of trying. But I learned a lot about math and logic in the interim. Programming requires very exact thinking which is the REAL benefit. People have often asked me why someone would learn programming since not everyone is going to be a programmer. Not everyone will be a COMPUTER programmer, everyone has the opportunity to use programming skills in daily life and jobs. Programming is breaking problems into their simplest components, and finding the most effective and efficient route to the answer, everything else is just syntax. I think this is why so many programmers lead super successful companies.
