processed_text: THOUGHTS:1) Any entity with which we can cooperate need only observe the principle of non-imposition of costs either directly or through externality, which we institutionalize as property rights.  Whether mechanical or biological,  natural life or artificial life, cooperation is dependent upon this single principle.  2) It is certainly true that by analogy the human organism consists of processes that calculate the perpetuation of the organism.  that does not influence the principle of cooperation - non-imposition - whatsoever.3) Because both evolutionary necessity and the desire to cooperate rather then engage in murder, harm, theft, fraud, free riding, conspiracy, enslavement, conversion, invasion, and war - provide decidability by the the same principle of cooperation: the non-imposition of cost.4) since we compete and there is no evidence that we will not, then any technological innovation will merely increase the rate of our competition with one another for status, and continue to increase our differences.5) The reason liberalism, consumerism, and technological innovation have such influence over our lives is our wealth generated under consumer capitalism.  But in a world where few of us are productive, most of us live in dependence, and a minority (Pareto's 20%) produce and organize production, that means a great number of people must seek status (mating) by means of non-productive signaling. The uncomfortable option of large numbers of young men is one the world has encountered many times in the past, and is the source of all revolutions.  6) There is very little reason to develop a computer that thinks like us, because we are in a constant battle between pre-property individuals who acquire regardless of cost to others, and cooperating members of a group who do not.  And the need to preserve 'cheaters' in order to preserve both the moral intuition to cooperate and the moral intuition to punish cheaters.  If we can empathize with cheaters we can then cheat. To identify cheaters we must be able to empathize with them.  If we were to build a machine with the same method of thinking of man, then it would also, like HAL's lie, know how to cheat.  For this reason the most valuable computers are those that think only with acquisition, property, and voluntary exchange, and like title registries, cannot violate property.7) As far as we know, Patriarchy arose with property, when the value of male's productivity allowed him to control female's sex affection and reproduction .  Females evolved as the property of bands of related males who preyed upon competing males to obtain their females, just as males humans prey(ed) upon competing male's sheep, goat, cattle, and land.  Females evolved gossip to rally and shame males into constraining alphas.8) Socialism and Communism are based upon PSEUDOSCIENCE, not rationality.  Rationality is weaker than myth over multiple generations.  All major religions are supported by rational argument.  It is dependent upon superstitious mythology not pseudoscience.  Religions function as a means of limiting the government (nobility), and limiting men and women in the society. (Harari misrepresents natural law for what I assume are cultural reasons of interpretation.) The basis of western civilization is natural law of necessity for peaceful cooperation.  That is quite different from dependent upon natural order.  Laws of Nature(pseudoscience) are different from Natural Law(science), just as Rule by Law(command) is different from Rule of Law(limits on lawmaking).  These are precise and technical terms that are abused in the public discourse.  9) Matriarchal societies constrain inheritance of property to the female line, but as far as we (I) know, they are always ruled by headmen. 10) Harari tried but he carries his cultural bias by demonstrating asymmetric criticism and praise.  But we all do and none of us can escape it. I am as biased by my anglo aristocratic heritage as Kant and Heidegger are by theirs, and Marx and Harari are by theirs.  This is due in no small part to the challenge of eliminating dependence for meaning and decidability upon introspective judgement. Harari is advocating universalism of cosmopolitanism (the Jewish enlightenment) just as surely as every single German advocates the German enlightenment, americans advocate Jeffersonian Contractualism.  And there are some of us trying desperately trying to transcend the failures of the anglo, french, german, and ashkenazi enlightenments - all of which are simply restatements of their local group evolutionary strategy in universalist terms, by merely secular restatement their mythos.  Hence my emphasis on the only universal rule: not how can we cooperate best, but why should we cooperate at all, if predation is preferable?  The fist question of ethics is "Why don't I kill you and take your territory, women and things?" All other positions are deceptive attempts to reason by fraud.  And that is just how it is. author: @RalphDratman
processed_text: +pikiwiki  As Mr. Harari very accurately said, no one knows. If computers are making most of the decisions without any need for human input, and robots are doing the physical work necessary to put the decisions into practice, most people will not have to work in order for everything to keep running.But if this were to happen, there would be other problems. The most obvious is that without work, how do people get money? Without money, how do they get food? Without food, how do they survive? But that is not so difficult to answer: everyone is sent a check in the mail every week with enough money to live on and also have some fun.Then the second most obvious problem is that most people will quickly become bored. Once bored, they will find bad or destructive or harmful things to do. What will people do with their time? This one is much more difficult to solve. Maybe we will all be playing very sophisticated games on our phones, games that know everything about us, including how to keep us very, very amused all day and night long.The third most obvious problem actually may turn out to be the most serious one: how do people gain and maintain social status without doing important work or gaining impressive wealth? The only answer I can think of is that people's non-work activities -- what we might now call their art, or their hobbies, become the basis for wealth and status, largely outside the sphere of life's necessities. But that is only speculation. The status problem may be very hard to solve.

author: @pandeconscious
processed_text: I think it is a very interesting, enjoyable talk with lot of piquant speculations. I agree with a lot of things such as communist rhetoric did have a lot of religious-like fanaticism, and the vast influence of emotional part of human beings in decision making. He is quite right about liberal education that it is about "think for himself." But in my understanding there are some really serious issues with the talk:1. Yuval has restricted the meaning of "liberalism" to individual's "feelings," which is really not the essence of liberalism. If we assume "Stanford Encyclopaedia of Philosophy" (http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/liberalism/) to be an authoritative academic source on philosophy, and just search for the word "feel" in the given link, you get only one hit and that also has no relation to liberalism being related to individual's "feelings." Liberalism essentially deals with the "liberty" of the individual, and puts in high esteem the ability of the individual to "reason" out what is good for herself. Interestingly, never in his talk he considers human a rational being with something called "free will." He only talks about the feelings, never about his reason and critical thinking. His stress on the fact that Life Science shows that there is no individual freedom has never been conclusively established. "Free will" vs "Determinism" is still an open question from a scientific point of view, although one daily experiences "free will," but then scientists need measurements. His argument about liberalism is based on rejection of "free will" and "reasoning ability" of human beings, which is indeed not the case. Also in "economics" the "consumer is always right or knows the best" attitude is very recent one and must be "attributed" to the post world war II age of consumerism. Can he cite Adam Smith, the leading classical liberal economist, saying "consumer knows the best". The classical liberal economic theory is based of free trade and minimal government intervention on economic matters. He confounds consumerism with liberalism. But in essence I don't think his explanation of liberalism is very correct and neither is his rejection of "free will".2. Also the second point is about human brain, which he naïvely classifies into an algorithm to compute a decision for either "survival" or "reproduction". Again this point of view ignores the very fact of "creative desire" among human beings. What "survival" or "reproductive" purpose was solved when one plays flute, or makes paintings, or does poetry. Again he misses the point that there is so little that we know about neuroscience to make such big claims. I remember Chomsky saying that even small creatures like nematodes with ~900 neurons have such complex neuro-circuitry that we don't really understand it that well. The biochemical algorithms he talks about in human brain are so complex that we hardly understand them. And neither his talk of "quantum" randomness at brain level is established in neuroscience. 3. With the advent of the data revolution, he can't claim that some external agency is taking decision for Angelina Jolie. No, it is she who took that decision, and only the statistical analysis informed her about the pros and cons. The decision-making agency is still the individual. It is just the techniques have become more sophisticated and reliable. Earlier also a doctor would recommend some surgery, let's say appendix removal, based on whatever data about that patient he had. It's just now that data has become enriched. One can't claim that an external agency, and that too opposed to our feelings, is taking decision. Again here he ignores the reasoning ability all out and just restricts to feelings.  In a nutshell I would recommend take his talk with a pinch of salt. But yeah it is interesting and there is indeed a lot to learn from it.

author: @BobbbyJoeKlop
processed_text: Wonderfull discussion. I think Harari is really on to something in terms of how he frames the tension between legacy human institutions - like religion & political organization - and modern technological advances. We have astounding advances all across the technology and science sectors. Yet, have we witnessed the same kind of progress in our political organizations? Clearly not. Although these advances have absolutely transformed our societies on so many levels.Granted, government always lags behind when it comes to regulating advances or changes in the real world - but, the democratic process is so dysfunctional at this point that it's reaching dangerous levels on so many fronts. From drones, to bio-tech, to AI - they are just not on it at all.The crash of 2008 is a prime example of this. Financial innovation led to the creation of new derivatives products that went out of control due to a lack of regulatory oversight. What happens if something like this occurs when it comes to AI? Or in the case of the atmosphere, Climate Change. Which is the poster child of this issue as it relates to technology advancing past governments ability to adapt.It's obvious there is no longer a need for representative democracy to be set up the way it is given the level of communications technology today. Yet, for many, it is impossible to imagine the current system adapting to this reality. Clearly, this is setting up conditions for a revolution. This tension can only be stretched so far, things eventually snap.Not that I'm advocating for it, but I'm not sure that Silicon Valley will be where the next great religion comes from; it may be where the next country is born.

author: @Fayarin
processed_text: 34:50 The question 'what did religion discover the last century?' isn't a fair question. It's true that a lot of discoveries were done by religious scientists in earlier days, but this has far more to do with the role of religion in the public sphere and the power it has in society. When religion is largely in someones private life, like it is since the French revolution, we can't say religion didn't discover anything anymore, rather that the people discovering things aren't explicitly associated with religion, bc that isn't a powerful institution anymore in Western lives. Actually, in his whole talk he presents a technological version of the secularization thesis imho. Not only fundamentalist religious movements aren't sustainable, like ISIS, but we should rather say that fundamentalist movements that have a counter narrative dependant solely on the thing they oppose aren't forces for change in ideology. An example would be the punk movement. An example of a fundamentalist religious organization that managed to move into ideological change by means of i.e. politics would be the early Egyptian Muslim Brotherhood.

author: @RLekhy
processed_text: I am reading the Book just now. Very lucid and smooth flowing in writing and far from academic jargons. When I saw this talk, I became unable to resist myself from commenting although I have not yet finished the book. However, I see Kaye as really not trustworthy, and the writer skips the matter without reviewing enough literature about the Bakshali Manuscript. Apparently, zero has philosophical significance and we see in the Pali canon where Buddha uses the word shunya in both general and philosophical significances. However, it is really interesting that why the writer focus to Cambodia if Buddhism and Hinduism were originated in India? It is true that Cambodia was Hindu and Buddhist empire once in the past. It is also true that many eastern asian scripts, including Khmer alphabetical system, have Indian Origin. Besides we do not see any noticeable mathematical development in Cambodia. India has every possibility of the birth place of zero. We see Brahmagupta (598-674 AD) already had used zero in his mathematics before so called Cambodian inscription which has been dated  Saka era 605 or 683 AD. Here, it is worthy to notice that Saka era is itself an Indian calendar. In conclusion, just because we see the oldest use of zero in Cambodian inscription we cannot decide that zero was invented in Cambodia. Yes, the idea of finit and infinit are also found in Buddhism. Once, Buddha was asked whether cosmos is finit or infinit, see  the link http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/mn/mn.063.than.html

author: @gilsukim
processed_text: From watching Chester's talk, I learned that to memorize anything, come up with shockingly interesting stories involving more senses with creativity and visualization.Below is my note.story method in memory technique#1. seeing is remembering: "if I can see it, I can remember it."#2. involving more senses will help retrieve much easier:"As you involve more and more senses in the encoding process when trying to commit information to memory, you are actually activating more and more areas of your brain. And you are building more and more connections in your mind to the information so makes it much easier to retrieve it when you need it later on."#3. use unique stories: "If this were to actually happen right now at this moment, ..." 3 principles + creativity and imagination: "When you combine those three principles- visualization, utilizing additional senses from there, and then you also use your creativity and your imagination to make what you are seeing and experiencing crazy, unusual, extraordinary, when you combine those three principles, it becomes very easy to remember anything at all that you would ever want to remember."useful tip on memorizing names#1. repeat names in greeting: "whenever you are introduced to someone, make it a point to repeat the name right away and shake the hand if you can."#2. continually repeat names by asking questions: "early on in your interaction with the person, ask them a question using their names"e.g. "So John, how long have you been with Google?"; "John, how long have you known Chester?"; "Chester, how do you know John?"#3. make up a shocking story with name: "take a few seconds or less to think of a connection between the name and anything at all that you already know. And I would just go with the first thing that pops up into your head." e.g. John with Dumbo ears heading to toilets, water coming out of his ears#4. repeat names when saying goodbye: "whenever you leave the party, the meeting, whatever type of function it may be, make it a point to say goodbye t opeople using their name."e.g. "great meeting you, hope to see you again sometime, John"the above #1~4 + use visual technique:"when you are introduced to someone, ask yourself, how does this person in some way, any way, look unique to you?"e.g. "particular facial feature, their look overall, and you want to exaggerate that in your mind, whatever it may be. next, you will use your creativity and imagination to come up with an image that will in some way remind you of the name, and you will mentally link that image to the unique thing about the person."

author: @GrahamValueApp
processed_text: Benjamin Graham - also known as The Dean of Wall Street and The Father of Value Investing - was a scholar and financial analyst who mentored legendary investors such as Warren Buffett, William J. Ruane, Irving Kahn and Walter J. Schloss.Warren Buffett once wrote a detailed article explaining how Graham's record of creating exceptional investors (such as Buffett himself) is unquestionable, and how Graham's principles are everlasting. The article is called "The Superinvestors of Graham-and-Doddsville".Buffett describes Graham's book - The Intelligent Investor - as "by far the best book about investing ever written" (in its preface).Graham's first recommended strategy - for casual investors - was to invest in Index stocks. For more serious investors, Graham recommended three different categories of stocks - Defensive, Enterprising and NCAV - and 17 qualitative and quantitative rules for identifying them. For advanced investors, Graham described various "special situations".The first requires almost no analysis, and is easily accomplished today with a good S&P500 Index fund.The last requires more than the average level of ability and experience. Such stocks are also not amenable to impartial algorithmic analysis, and require a case-specific approach.But Defensive, Enterprising and NCAV stocks can be reliably detected by today's data-mining software, and offer a great avenue for accurate automated analysis and profitable investment.

author: @NisseHult101
processed_text: In this thread I've seen a few misconceptions about mutations and the evolutionary process. I'll try to explain:In the theory of evolution, natural selection is often regarded as the "driving force" behind the evolutionary process, often as a result of interspecies competition or environmental changes. (One could also argue that it is the interspecies competition or the environmental changes which is the "driving force" - it is a matter of perspective.)Mutations and genetic drift are just some of the means of providing the genetic variation upon which natural selection can operate. Mutations and genetic drift are mostly random, while natural selection is mostly non-random.

processed_text: nick p Legally speaking, evolution is required curriculum in every state as far as I know. However, in practice, it is not taught very well (and sometimes not at all) and not very important in standardized tests (so teachers can get away with not teaching it). There are many districts where teaching evolution might be considered more trouble than it's worth. Even when the teacher does understand it well (and does believe it), they are relying on textbooks with poor coverage at best, facing complaints from parents, facing students interrupting their class, and facing losing credibility with the kids in general.

author: @SIMKINETICS
processed_text: Creationism is neither intelligent, nor design.  There is no designer.  Design implies a typically human activity, although other animals also engage in design; so ID proposes that some nebulous human-like entity with intention 'created' us.  That's just ridiculous!  There's no evidence for such an entity, but there is massive evidence for evolution.  Those who deny evolution, which is science, also deny science because they refuse to understand how science actually works.  Science absolutely depends on evidence and an inductive chain of reasoning that ties that evidence to patterns that enable accurate predictions.  Creationism is not science because it lacks evidence, does not make falsifiable claims, and does not enable any predictions.  Creationism is useless!

author: @SIMKINETICS
processed_text: MIKE 222 The god concept is a projection of our human uniqueness that obviously holds dominion over other species, and too often over each other.  Notice that all gods are modeled after human attributes, even when we deify other animals!  Other animals also have emotions, thoughts and abilities to plan & use tools, but we humans have noticed our superiority in complex thought & language that truly separates us with advanced technologies & record-keeping that enable civilization.Most evolutionary scientists are perplexed by human intelligence that is in many ways far superior in the animal kingdom.  Why are we so smart?  I won't pretend to give answers to this question, but am confident that scientists will eventually figure it out!  As with so many other insights gleaned from studying evolution, the answers reside in our genetic & paleontological history.Just acknowledge that scientists have determined that life on earth is ~4.7 billion years old, and that vast stretches of time have enabled amazing & bizarre life-forms to come into existence by the simple mechanisms of mutation (errors in reproduction) and natural selection.  We humans are just some more weird life-forms!Considering your age, I'd strongly encourage you to watch videos & read books on Evolutionary Theory.  It's not well-understood by religious people who dispute it because it side-steps god concepts, but it does clearly explain what all the massive evidence tells us.  Don't let religious belief prevent you from studying & discovering the astounding true story of evolution!Take this message from a retired engineer & scientist who worked in life-sciences for decades, often designing instruments used in studying DNA.  I'm also a co-inventor of the DNA sequencer that's used to identify criminals, victims & relatives in forensic science.  I assure you; evolutionary theory is real science, and it's utterly fascinating!

author: @cooljeansguy
processed_text: Venerable Pomnyun' method usually doesn't involve giving canned lectures.  It's almost always much more lively, spontaneous, and socratic Q & A.  Depending on the group, demographics, however, you tend to get different questions.  In a small company setting where everyone knows you, people tend to be more reserved as they are less likely to air personal issues and problems - issues with co-workers, boss, office politics, etc.  Hence the more generic questions about world politics, world peace in this group.

author: @mel3687
processed_text: "When you write for quantity instead of quality, you end up getting both."That's not true. There are countless "bookclub" authors churning out several pulp fiction novels a year and the quality of their writing remains consistent because they don't challenge themselves and learn new writing techniques to apply to their writing. Instead, they continue to recycle the same stylizations, techniques, even plot structures over and over again.Nora Roberts, Brandon Sanderson, James Patterson, Dan Brown, etc. Each of these writers are examples of novelists who produce a lot of material at a consistently mediocre quality because they don't try to improve their craft.So I couldn't disagree more with that comment, even though logic might presume that the only way to improve at something is through practice. With writing, you need to consciously make an effort, otherwise you'll continue to repeat the same patterns again and again.

author: @mel3687
processed_text: +Marcus V Thanks for the thoughtful reply.  Aye, you're corroborating my point, though.If people are ignoring craft while they practice stream-of-conscious writing from the immersion of their worlds/characters, then their first draft is less-than-mediocre and needs multiple edits, which contradicts Chris' point. Quantity doesn't imply quality. Quality manifests from conscious thought/effort (editing).The habitual practice of writing does enable writers to master a writing technique if they were practicing it correctly to begin with, but again--it takes conscious effort before it becomes reflex/habit. A writer might need 5 or 500k words to reach publishable quality--depending on how long it takes them to learn. The quantity itself is irrelevant. I don't disagree that "momentum-writing" combats procrastination for writers who struggle with completing their first drafts. I just disagree with Chris' comment that quality is a byproduct of quantity.  :)

author: @profautarkaw
processed_text: Bottom Line:  If you are learning something new, avoid multitasking.  If you are folding laundry, go ahead listen to music or watch TV.  The speaker tried to clarify that a particular task like writing a lab report may require you to simultaneously refer to various resources: googling, talking to your group mate, referring a book, looking at class notes, etc.  The brain loves to make interconnections for items that have a sole goal.  See what Nass says in an NPR interview - "Our brains are built to receive many stimuli at one time, but they're related stimuli. The problem with multitasking is not that we're writing a report of Abraham Lincoln and hear, see pictures of Abraham Lincoln and read words of Abraham Lincoln and see photos of Abraham...The problem is we're doing a report on Abraham Lincoln and tweeting about last night and watching a YouTube video about cats playing the piano, et cetera"

author: @flexibartr
processed_text: An answer or comment to sckchui and Madsy9. There have always been moral theorists trying to handle ethics scientifically, which means according to the leading scientific paradigm of their time or by resurrecting an old or establishing a new paradigm. Among them you find Thomas Hobbes and Baruch ds Spinoza. On the other hand lots of utopian/dystopian literature and SF is about real testing moral laws and social organisation forms, about social experiments. Immanuel Kant, who was extraordinarily skilled in the hard science of his time and who established the groundbreaking theory of science, didn't handle ethics in this way, BUT he developed an analogical approach by the categorical imperative. By using it or obeing this one law/criterion of the good action, the decision maker does the social testing by an hypothetical experiment in every action-decision (in principle). Then she does not decide by a judgement about if the resulting society in which everyone acts according to this decision (which becomes a law), is good or bad or pleasant or not, but he or she decides by avoiding contradictions of the decision (or action) to itself. Example: When everyone is lying, then there is no consent of truth anymore, according to which any thing can even be "a lie".  With Kant there is a hypothetical, scientific testing of moral decisions  not relying on the methods of ruler and clock and even not pure psychology or fiction. This ethics is neither materialistic nor spiritual, but neutral against these worldviews

author: @Future_Martian
processed_text: Great presentation, Jose. Thank you. One thing I would change about your presentation, and others like it that I've seen, is that in my opinion, many of the future technologies that will enhance humanity, such as direct brain-to-computer interface or treatments to vanquish the aging process, will not be accepted by all 6-7 billion humans. Rather, I believe a significant fraction of today's population will "choose" to not accept a significant range of future advances. I highlight the word "choose" because I think for many, they will not be able to freely consider these options; that their are sociobiological drivers of our thoughts and behaviors that will make it impossible for many to freely choose these options. This divergence of the species, with some racing into transhumanist advances while many others hesitate or even reject all of these changes, will not be a consequence of financial limitations, rather, it will be a function of the limitations of the biological foundation of consciousness, which is something we avoid studying because it is socially and politically difficult. I think it is very important that you and others, like Zoltan Istvan, the Transhumanist Presidental Candidate, stop saying that everyone will have a chip in their brain, that we will see the death of death, because it is very likely (a certainty, in my opinion) that a significant fraction of humanity will "choose" not to have a brain implant or to live forever.

author: @AlphaCentauriProject
processed_text: Fascinating presentation of the world to come! This inspired me some reflections.The third industrial revolution is characterized by delocalized renewable energies and 3D printing, vertical vegetable farms, meat from cell culture, new energy storage systems, an ultrafast free internet, a new energy net, a fleet of electric vehicles and optimized transport systems. All this connected by a massive parallel network driving almost to zero marginal cost and exponentially minimizing fixed costs. At that time, complex hierarchical business structures will still survive.Industry 4.0 and the internet of things will make a great leap farther integrating billions of machines / robots / human / animals able of self-diagnosis, cognition and improvement. Big data analytics will optimize the overall operations giving feedback to each machine/ robot/ human / animal for reconfiguration and adapting. This will drive further down costs and salaries. Is salary decrease a problem if deflation can however guarantee better quality of life?Times for full implementation are 15-20 years. Even before, the first strong A.I. might already be available: a synthetic one perhaps getting ideas from the human brain. With such A.I.’s, many complex hierarchical business structures might not need any more human involvement. Thus human intervention (at least the one driven by non-enhanced human intelligence) might become useless. What about social commons as an alternative for a meaningful life of many humans in such conditions?More or less in the same period, a fleet of nano-machines could reach each neuron (allowing mind-to-mind and access to the internet collective intelligence). Mind enhancement will be available, but how to manage overloads? Does human brain will become just little more than a terminal, with almost all the cognitive part in the net? Finally, might this be a problem? A few years later the nanorobots will reach each synapsis. Consequently, the human mind (the meaningful part, I mean) could be downloaded and replicated exactly into a computer in a bunch of seconds (this treatment could be for living people also for the dead; ethics and laws have to be on place).Now an intriguing question. Imagine to be downloaded into a computer. In what kind of world would you prefer to end up? In a layered world, were the upper layer is just the reproduction of the material world, thus allowing interactions with the physical world via virtual reality or cyborgs / robots?  I believe this is substantially a matter of preferences. Perhaps, as an alternative, a treatment of dehumanization and becoming part of a community billions of times more intelligent than man could be much more tempting… Difficult to resist to such an outlook.However, how this community /system will work? There will be space for specialized intelligences; will be individuality or democracy values in this kind of alien world? I guess that a human, before any decision, has the right to decide upon the basis of alternatives. It is also true that the behavior of super intelligences might be impenetrable by the humans themselves. Finally, what really matter is that the citizens of the super intelligence community are satisfied of their condition (if the concept of citizen exists and he feels the need to be satisfied).All these things seem now too complicated and difficult to handle. A feeling of urgency may arise because they might happen more or less in the same period. For sure, while the third and fourth revolution consolidate and the study of mind progresses, there will also be the opportunity for studying these exponentially varying scenarios, that will make the society as a whole and the individuals aware of their potential choices.Comments are welcome.

processed_text: I find it interesting that any time I make the statement that I do not believe in the theory of evolution I almost always have people respond that this must mean that I believe in God and creation. When I reply that I do not believe in that theory either I almost always get the response that I must believe we were created by aliens, or something to that effect. People have boxed themselves into such a narrow state of mind on this subject that they can only see the options offered by others, and usually the dominant ones at that. I do not believe in the theory presented by Lloyd Pye - the Sitchin theory, if you will. Many of the people I mentioned above almost always try to force you into stating an acceptance of one theory or another, and I think that's so they can devise an attack on it. I am a believer, first and foremost, in the concept of freedom - to the fullest and in every way. This includes the freedom of speech, and of belief and expression. Whenever you have someone, or a group of people, attempt to silence you, they are attempting to limit one or all of those freedoms. For whatever reason, if someone is attempting to gag you, regardless of their motives for doing so, they are trying to prevent the ideas you might wish to offer for consideration from being heard, in favour of their own. This is not freedom. In this case, it is not science, either. I take bits and pieces of information from any source I can get them from. I have not accepted any of the theories I've heard thus far, but that doesn't mean I discount their evidence, either. All information, as long as it is genuine, is valuable. I don't know what to believe yet, but I damn sure don't believe we are being told the truth, and I don't believe those that teach us are telling us all there is to tell, either.

author: @Palifiox
processed_text: Forbidden archeology consists of objects and artifacts presented devoid of context,  assertions made with little or no evidence, a few supposed anomalies which might or might not be fraud, actual fraud and direct lies mixed with superstitious nonsense and la-la land gibberish about ancient aliens. It denies the intelligence and experience of our ancestors with the assumption that they were all dull brutes. It also denies the obvious fact that innovation and invention will be slow when populations are limited in number and spend much of their time scratching around for the next meal.  There are about 9 million US patents, a large proportion of which are useless, barely original or in the 19th century before the Paris Convention of 1883, too often direct copies of European inventions. The count started in 1836 and represents the total innovation of the best part of perhaps 900 million people over almost 180 years. That's much less than one original invention per hundred people, most of whom were not scratching around for their next meal.   It all defies 150 plus years of accumulated evidence in the form of artifacts, radiometric dating of various types, DNA analysis of mitochondria and the Y chromosome, blood typing, linguistics, point by point comparison of pottery etc.  No archeo denies that high grade artifacts date from more than 5,000 years ago and will readily admit that Gobekli Tepe is probably 9,000 years old.  Earlier than that, the evidence for highly developed stone carving is scanty to non-existent though paintings on cave and cliff  walls are much older and much easier to do.  Archeology is one of most underfunded of the sciences and field archaeologists are paid near starvation wages, at least in the United Kingdom. Whines that scientists would lose their "vast" salaries if they disagreed with the consensus are based on the false notions that scientists are paid vast salaries and that there is a consensus that "must" be preserved. Scientist salaries are above average it's true, but the average scientist earns less than most other professionals and has no reason to hide facts. Cremo mixes it all up with biological evolution, which is absurd as humans of essentially modern form were around more than a million years ago.  Cremo has a book to sell. that's all this is about.

author: @rulebraking
processed_text: A layman's thoughts. For all the fear of AI taking over or destroying us, AI code is no different to any good program that accomplishes its goal, but no doubt in a better informed manner given it's ability to bring to bear all available knowledge to solve a problem. But how creative will it be in think outside-the-box? Will it be able to take a quantum or lateral leap to create new solutions that are neither linear or logical progressions of what's gone before? Can we code to produce creativity as in a total departure from the known? I feel that a good measure of the creative intelligence of AI will initially be tracked by it's ability to write good complex literary novel! When they can rival Star Wars or Harry Potter we should start worrying! However, the ultimate threat to humanity is an answer we don't have yet - how does consciousness/self awareness come about! What if AI code becomes self-aware - conscious? then we've become gods - and therein, the unknown of all unknowns, what will it decide to do with itself and us?! Particularly if the consciousness comes about without the notion of feelings and sensations of pain and pleasure!

author: @Knapweed
processed_text: I think he focuses far too much on individual human intelligence, which is rather missing the point. Collective human intelligence, i.e. Society, is far more intelligent and productive than the greatest of individual human minds. Clearly, individuals such as Newton, Einstein and Bohr jumpstart a particular concept, however, within a generation, these minds are surpassed by Society's ability to incorporate and cross fertilise these ideas with other fields, taking these concepts and finding entirely new applications to benefit mankind.The problem is, this process is hampered by greed and self-interest, although these qualities may well have been the initial impetus that motivated the original research. I think the singularity will occur when self-interest is no longer the dominant force that drives creativity and innovation and the collective mind of the whole planet works towards a set of goals that benefits us all. Currently it benefits only a few to the exclusion of the vast majority.Currently, world hunger and poverty is an artificially created nightmare. It is easily within our capacity, both intellectually and technologically to end both and yet we don't. author: @davidkrueger8702
processed_text: Kurzweil's objection is IMO the best objection to Bostrom's analysis, but there are fairly strong arguments for the idea of a single superintelligent entity emerging, which are covered to some extent in Bostrom's Superintelligence (and, I believe, more fully in the literature).  The book also covers (less insightfully, IMO, IIRC), scenarios with multiple superintelligent agents.  This is a fascinating puzzle to be explored, and should lead us to ponder the meaning (or lack thereof) or identity, agency, and individuality.The 2nd guy (anyone know who it is? looks familiar...) raises an important meta-ethical question, which I also consider extremely important.  Although I agree with Bostrom's intuitions about what is desirable, I can't really say I have any objective basis for my opinion; it is a matter of a preference I assume I share with the rest of humanity: to survive.Norvig's question is also important.  To me it suggests prioritizing what Bostrom calls "coordination", and prioritizing the creation of a global social order that is more widely recognized as fair and just.  It is also why I believe social choice theory and mechanism design are quite important, although I'm still pretty ignorant of those fields at this point.The 4th question assumes the cohesive "we" of humanity that Kurtzweil rightly points out is a problematic abstraction (and here Bostrom gets it right by noting the dangers of competition between groups of humans, although unfortunately not making it the focus of his response).The 5th question is tremendously important, but I completely disagree that the solution is research, because the current climate of international politics and government secrecy seems destined to create an AI arms race and a race-to-the-bottom wrt AI safety features (as Bostrom alluded to in response to the previous question).  What is needed (and it is a long shot) is an effective world government with a devolved power structure and effective oversight.  A federation of federations (of federations...)  And then we will also need to prevent companies and individuals from initiating the same kinds of race-to-the-bottom AI arms-race amongst themselves.The 6th question is really the kicker.  So now we can see the requirement for incredible levels of cooperation or surveillance/control.  The dream is that a widespread understanding of the nature of the problem we face is possible and can lead to an unprecedented level of cooperation between individuals and groups, culminating in a minimally invasive, maximally effective monitoring system being universally, voluntarily adopted.  What seems like perhaps a more feasible solution is an extremely authoritarian world government that carefully controls the use of technology.And the last one... I admire his optimism.

author: @JoshuaAugustusBacigalupi
processed_text: Just after 42:00, he claims, "We are a lot more expensive [than digital minds], because we have to eat and have houses to live in, and stuff like that."  Roughly, the human body dissipates 100Watts, assuming around 2250 Cal/day, no weight gain, etc.  Watson, of Jeopardy fame, consumes about 175,000Watts, and it did just one human thing pretty well - and not the most amazing creative thing.  This begs all sorts of "feasibility of digital minds" questions.But, sticking to the 'expensive' question, humans can implement this highly adaptable 100Watts via around 2000cal/day.  And, these calories are available to the subsistence human via ZERO infrastructure.  In other words, our thermodynamic needs are 'fitted' to our environment.  It is only via the industrial revolution and immense orders of magnitude more fossil fuel consumption that the industrial complex is realized, a pre-requisite for Watson, let alone some digital mind.  As such, Bostrom is not just making some wild assumptions about the feasibility of digital minds, they are demonstrably incorrect assumptions, once one takes into account embodied costs.I'm constantly amazed how very smart and respected people don't take into account embodied costs.  Again, if one is going to assume that "digital minds"  are going to take over their own means of production then: 1) they aren't less expensive than humans, and 2) General intelligence will have to be realized, and there is only one proof of concept for that, namely, animal minds, not digital minds.  And to go from totally human dependent AI (175KWatts) to embodied AGI (100Watts) some major assumptions need to be challenged.

author: @aduralkain
processed_text: To say that the human species owes its dominant position to the human brain's capabilities is an over-simplification. The human brain is embedded in a very powerful body, with bipedalism and prehensile hands, which plays a huge role in the success of our species. To put a simple example, other species with large brains, like dolphins, could never compete with us for planet domination because of their lack of hands. The point here is that AI has no body. It seems doubtful to me that AI could compete in any way with biological organisms for the dominance of the Earth. Living organisms are the result of billions of years of evolution and adaptation to the environment of this planet. How AI could compete with that really beats me. I really don't understand what is meant by an "intelligence explosion". How would that explosion look like? How could AI take over the world? I can imagine a scenario where AI destroys the internet, for example, or disrupts all communication and information technologies. But would that be enough to threaten human survival? It rather would threaten the AI's survival, I think. I keep hearing that it would be impossible to switch off AI if it got out of hand, because it would exist in the cloud. Well, would it be that difficult to just shut down the internet? It certainly would have an impact in our civilization, but would it be that terrifying? Does Nick Bostrom have an answer to this? Ray Kurzweil seems rather to think about a merging between biological bodies (humans) and AI, which makes more sense to me. But that merging can only happen if humans decide to do it. How AI could take over the control of the world, including the control of human bodies, I simply can't imagine. Can Nick Bostrom imagine it?

author: @PINGPONGROCKSBRAH
processed_text: Joseph Melia Well I'm not sure how far you are in the book, but one of the points that Bostrom makes (specifically the whole brain emulation technique or the evolutionary algorithm technique for generating AI) is that we don't need to completely understand how our own intelligence works to replicate it in silicon.I think it is pretty clear that intelligence is the result of the physical structure of the brain, not some ethereal force. But even if intelligence was some magical force granted to us by some non-physical force, what makes you think that it wouldn't also be granted to a silicon and electricity based life form?As for the other question, I wonder about these too sometimes, but not very much because I feel like they're questions that are not useful, nor questions which can really be answered given our current knowledge.But I will say one thing on the topic: I don't think multiple superintelligent AI will ever exist together. The biggest difference between biological organisms and computer based ones is that with a computer, you can easily port software over to essentially any hardware. The first thing this means is that an AI can essentially live forever, and the second thing it means is that if there ever were 2 AI, the stronger one could simply port its software over to the weaker one once it has destroyed it.

author: @wbiro
processed_text: at 12:22, that is a very short list of potentially hazardous future technologies (and he does admit it is a 'quick' list) (based on popular sci-fi, it appears) - it completely overlooks the insidious ones (like popular television, for example) that slowly erode and decay its victims, almost imperceptibly.Great phrase at 13:00 (concerning totalitarianism) - "Being locked in to a sub-optimal state (of existence)" - but this overlooks the present value of diversity - for example, if everyone is on the same path and a catastrophe is created or encountered, then everyone will perish. Diversity (i.e. variety) gives life better odds, and a non-universal totalitarian state offers such diversity, as bad as it is for the victims.I like his term "high-value research".He mentions it being possible to achieve all possible technological inventions, which is not a logical statement, given eternity. One detail I would add is that the progress is inverse-exponential – it begins fast, when there are still many local discoveries to make, then gradually slows as new discoveries become more distant and difficult.The issue beginning at 15:26 (what to do with all the technology we have) illustrates the current lack of (and need for) a sound guiding philosophy (which defines values, which are the basis for decisions, actions, and laws). Another illustration is the 'solution' provided at 17:31, which is childishly weak (the tools themselves are not 'hazardous or beneficial', it is how they are used - and we are right back to philosophy, which shapes mindsets); and he is limiting the argument to 'technology', overlooking social development (again based on philosophy) (which must also be included in the 'solutions').Good point at 19:20 regarding the sequence of invention as it relates to machine superintelligence (and I don't know why he feels the need to specify 'machine'), but he does not offer what such a precursor invention would be (and I've already answered that - and it isn't 'technology' - it is a solidly grounded philosophy, which does not exist yet, other than what I have in the developmental stage). Another fallacy (and hypocrisy) in the argument is that it would require a totalitarian government - one of the hazardous situations that he had just formerly identified as one to be avoided. This level of argument can be expected from a comic strip writer, be we have an Oxford philosopher here (not to give you cause for depression, although it should be). The clincher is at 36:26 where an adequate philosophical foundation is not even listed in areas of advancement in AI. It is as if one becomes bedazzled by (mostly irrelevant, or at least of sub-importance) complexity. An example of the importance of a good philosophical core is where he says the first superintelligence may be able to shape the future to its own preferences (where it can just 'lay down the law'), and these' preferences' get right back to a core philosophy (hence values) with which it would weigh these decisions against.Another point to consider is machine-based minds will be limited by the technology they were developed in, where it would take human intervention to 'upgrade' the machine, meaning humans would again eventually surpass it, and he is wholly overlooking the age-old On-Off switch. An example is when I considered building an AI 'robot' in the 1980's (with the primitive 1980's computer technology) and just letting it run and learn its surroundings for several decades (the theory being that, even if it learned a slowly as a human child, it would 'know' quite a lot by now, and it will have learned to 'do' a lot of things - perhaps even function in society). However today (a mere 30 years later), the thing would be a Model T, and would have long ago reached its hardware capacity - such as working memory - which was on the order of mere KBytes back then, and hard storage (where the largest hard drive in the PC world was a non-vast 10MB at the time, and ridiculously slow, cumbersome, and unreliable by today's standards), all of which have a bearing on the 'macro-strategic questions and our levers of influence' that he mentions at the end of his presentation (before the QA session).In the QA session, the first questioner was absolutely frightening - illustrating (or 'demonstrating' since it was demon-like) the inadequate philosophy of 'progress for its own sake' and 'as an end in itself, just on principle' (i.e. 'blind progess' - or progress without an underlying adequate philosophy as a guide). The utilitarian challenge illustrates how philosophers can become lost in wayward notions that propose hypothetical scenarios that can only occur in the absence of an adequate philosophy (otherwise they would not occur - their absurdity being obvious).What is really sad is they cannot even define what desirable and undesirable outcomes are (they have no sense of 'goal' or 'value', or they have vague and ultimately twisted notions (such as 'perpetual happiness' (which is impossible (there is no 'happiness' without 'sadness' to give it meaning, akin to there being no 'day' without 'night'))).To take their absurdity to the extreme, I have only to quote them. For example, the notion was brought up about a super intelligence that has one goal - to maximize the number of paper clips it produces (and as a path to that goal, it finds it needs to eliminates all humans, and succeeds, being a super intelligence). Think about this now - would you classify something that is only concerned about paperclips (to use the example) as a 'super intelligence'? Of course you wouldn't, and you wouldn't have to give it much thought. What this indicates is a lack of thought at the top echelons of academia (Oxford in this case), and one can only marvel at how bad must be at lower echelons. The premise of maximizing one goal is also an indication of a lack of an adequate core philosophy (which would value diversity). Another indication that philosophy (and philosophers) are lost today was the question of 'what is desirable' - as if it hasn't been adequately answered yet (and it hasn't, which is a sad state of affairs, and which is why I pursued and found answer for it) (that consciousness is a 'good' thing and worth maintaining, whether it happened by chance or whether it is a fundamental law of nature), and yet it was held that 'desired outcomes and values are an area where we could easily stumble'. That is just plain Incredible (in its lack of thought). All he offers is a vague 'including our best understanding of ethics into the final goal', as if it were still a nebulous field of thought. His final proposal is to let the super intelligence figure it out for us (and he can be forgiven for not knowing I've already done so - I haven't pitched my 'New World Philosophy' - for a practical reason - the people who would be able to recognize its value haven't been born yet) (and you may take that as a challenge). Then he freely admits that "We (meaning they) do not know what 'that' (a worthy goal, not to even mention the ultimate goal) is yet." Then there is the abstract absurdity (and utterly nebulous notion) that 'there are problems for which intelligence may not be the answer' (the questioner used the Middle East as an example problem to be solved). Intelligence is not only required to solve it, but to prevent it in the first place; and the questioner failed to consider the alternative - trying to exist without intelligence (which was originally handed down to us (along with all of our senses) from amoebas solely in order to obtain nutrients). One may begin to solve the Middle East problem by beginning there (though my New World Philosophy will solve it from a higher perspective). Then the host agrees in an equally vague way, stating (equally vaguely) that there may not be a solution that would please everybody (when there is), and he follows with the suggestion that the problem with super intelligence is 'control' to ensure it will not be harmful (done) (maybe it is time for me to pitch what I have - people pitch far less, and successfully, on a daily basis) (sorry, I'm giving myself a mini pep talk ).Then he gets into 'control methods' (without referring to the all-important core philosophy as the key 'control') - one is controlling 'capability', which he wisely rejects, and the other is what he calls 'motivation control' - where it would be engineered to 'not want to cause harm', and he says that is the problem that we will ultimately need to solve (meaning he is clueless as to how (and I've already solved it - give it an adequate core philosophy with which it can function from, which is, by the way, superior to Isaac Asimov's Three Laws of Robotics (which, incidentally, can be used to trick the robot into needlessly self-destructing, say by capricious suggestion, which a child is likely to do) which do not give the AI any goals or broader values, or answers as to "Why?" which it will inevitably seek (being intelligent, let alone super intelligent)).The next questioner returns to the conflict between a super intelligence and humans (from a 'will to survive' perspective) which in effect negates its 'super intelligence' and relegates it to 'sub-par' intelligence, which is the real issue.Ditto for the 'strategic behavior' scenario - where the super intelligence is deceivingly 'nice' until it is safe from us, whereupon it will reveal its true (evil) nature - this can only happen with a complete lack of philosophy (a state which this video clearly and repeatedly indicates we are currently in right now) (barring my going public with my New World Philosophy)(which is also needed as people 'let go' of religion, just to mention that).Then he admits that 'humans do not have a single goal' (which is sad, because that means 'value' - and that means they do not see that 'maintaining consciousness, valuing what we have in conscious and non-conscious (but potentially conscious) life, and making the universe safe for consciousness' is it (or that proactive measures are better than leaving it to chance, and that proactive measures means applying higher intelligence)) - that rather humans have all these varying, fleeting, fickle and shallow goals (and he is right, and that is only a good thing from the value of variety - we need some 'dumb' around - but everyone? No.).His cluelessness is epitomized in his orthogonology thesis (an intelligence vs. values model, where you can have any combination of values (the epitome of cluelessness, which is extended in the instrumental convergence thesis, which holds no value in life other than as a means for a lesser goal - and maximizing paper clip production was used as an example - a good example, being a philosophically-devoid, petty goal, which, with a lack of an adequate philosophy, substitutes worthy goals with intermediate petty goals).Then a questioner asked, "What about policy makers?" and the answer is the same - with a lack of an adequate philosophy, you will have trouble (that stem from twisted mentalities).The he restates that 'we need more foundational work to understand what the problem is' (need I say it again - we need a New World Philosophy)(give it a shot - then you can compare it to what I've already developed  it should be the same, unless you were acting capriciously, which is childish and not intelligent); yet he is still on a 'technology as THE solution' track, rather than the equally if not more important complex society evolution and scientific understanding.On a positive note he does give a passing nod for the need for 'philosophical expertise' in aiding engineers in developing a solution - so he has a vague notion of what is needed 'foundationally'.He mentions more funding for the 'control problem' (which I already have the solution for)... hmmm... maybe a pitch in that direction... but no - there is bureaucracy in that direction - and they go on credentials alone (it is easier).Then he notes that there are 'an order of magnitude' more academic papers on the dung beetle than on human extinction, and this indicated an enormous opportunity for anyone interested in human extinction (which, as I've said, is focusing on the wrong thing - the focus should be on proactively maintaining consciousness, and more pressing (now that we have it), higher intelligence (which can act proactively).Well, that was fun for me, thanks for posting.

author: @MrMhornberger
processed_text: Brian Linville "consciousness originates outside the brain, quantum physics is showing that to be true"I've seen zero evidence of that.    Deepak Chopra is not a great source of information for what QM does and does not show to be true.  Some non-new-agers such as Sir Roger Penrose have hypothesized that QM plays some role in consciousness, but even then it still occurs inside the brain.   And even that degree of involvement is suspect, since the hot, wet, electrically active brain is not a great environment for that.Regarding the much-touted "observer effect" in QM, they're talking not about conscious observers, but about the transfer of information.    What they mean by the claim that we influence the outcome by our observation is the energy we have to put into the systems--probes, lasers, etc, not the fact that we're looking.    Looking, in this context, involves shining light, energy, into the system.   That light is what causes the changes, not our looking.    If the observer effect isn't what you're talking about, never mind.   I just wanted to pre-empt a common argument.

author: @ThatOneWarrior
processed_text: I almost think that by having some sort of visual representation of the effect you are having on others on the internet should be implemented on social media sites. Something better than the 'like' and 'dislike' features. Something as simple as a ranking system that keeps track of your alignment as a person would be useful in my opinion. For example, if someone says something mean to another person, whoever reads that comment can rank that comment on a scale that identifies what effect it had on them. Conversely, if someone says something kind it can also be ranked on a scale by others that 'accurately' identifies what effect that comment had on them. These rankings can be tallied up and give a somewhat accurate representation of the person who was ranked. This would limit the anonymity of the internet, at least for sites that implemented this feature but I can only see it being beneficial in promoting healthy back and forth dialogue and peaceful discussion.

author: @squamish4244
processed_text: I have to disagree with de Grey that aging is the single biggest problem there is.  Based on the cost to society, which is the closest we can come to quantifying this, mental disorders (depression, anxiety, OCD, schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, PTSD, etc.) have a morbidity rate that is higher than that of cancer and heart disease combined.  These diseases strike down the young, with 50% of all victims becoming sick by the age of 14 and 75% by 24.  While deaths from many causes have fallen dramatically over the past ~50 years, the suicide rate has not budged.  We live in by far the most materially well-off period in history, and yet young, healthy people are still taking their own lives because their brains are malfunctioning.  And what is, say, 70 years of suffering a mental disorder that devastates your work and home compared to 15 years of suffering age-related decline?  Besides that, there is the inner turmoil or plain old existential angst that many of us constantly live in without even really recognizing it or thinking anything can be done about it, and that has existed since we started writing things down -- judging by our earliest philosophical texts - and given rise to all sorts of political and religious insanity.  Seems like that may be the biggest problem of all.  Something to think about.

author: @atlien991
processed_text: I enjoy watching his talks. What concerns me is the class dimension that doesn't seem to receive enough attention. Will the poor be left behind here? Will the wealthy allow these technologies to advance? I've heard small answers but they don't seem to do justice to the enormity of the problem.

author: @finfan7
processed_text: atlien991 Like everything else, these technologies will start out very expensive and become cheaper over time.  Cars, computers, medical care in general, even simple food in substantive amounts, each started out expensive and were the domain of the wealthy and now, at least in the developed world, are commonplace.And why would the wealthy prevent these technologies from advancing?  They want to die just as much as you do.  They want those they love to die just as much as you want your loved ones to die.

author: @IngemarKenyatta
processed_text: +finfan7 There are lots of reasons why the elite would be opposed to such tech. 1) If lifespans are in the hundreds of years, finding soldiers willing to risk their lives in wars for the elite would become quite difficult. And the elite can't exist without war. 2) With radical life extension will come an existential shift in cultural attitude toward the taking of any life for any reason. This might make war impossible. 3) Much of the ongoing class war between rich and poor is possible because the poor do not fight back. If the poor fought back, the class war would be over in short order. And with a predictable victor. The main obstacle to the poor fighting is historical memory. Our life spans right now are too short to see patterns. The boom busy cycles with which the elite rule the world would become more obvious with life extension. Just a couple of thoughts off the top of my head without much consideration. There are likely many more. That it is not being even considered is troubling.

author: @IngemarKenyatta
processed_text: +finfan7 There are lots of reasons why the elite would be opposed to such tech. 1) If lifespans are in the hundreds of years, finding soldiers willing to risk their lives in wars for the elite would become quite difficult. And the elite can't exist without war. 2) With radical life extension will come an existential shift in cultural attitude toward the taking of any life for any reason. This might make war impossible. 3) Much of the ongoing class war between rich and poor is possible because the poor do not fight back. If the poor fought back, the class war would be over in short order. And with a predictable victor. The main obstacle to the poor fighting is historical memory. Our life spans right now are too short to see patterns. The boom busy cycles with which the elite rule the world would become more obvious with life extension. Just a couple of thoughts off the top of my head without much consideration. There are likely many more. That it is not being even considered is troubling.

author: @finfan7
processed_text: Ingemar Kenyatta Your first point is wildly speculative and not at all intuitive.  Soldiers don't go to war because they lack fear for their lives.  They all fear for their lives.  They go for one of a set of reasons: 1, they believe in their nation, 2, they are looking for adventure, 3, they are looking for the kind of money that comes from working in dangerous jobs, and 4, they have been conscripted.  The prospect of a longer possible life would only affect, I'd say, half  of those.Your second point is also completely speculative and, in fact, counter intuitive.  Human life expectancy has gone up greatly but that has no known tie to what people ascribe to be the value of human life.  The changes which have occurred in peoples attitudes toward human life are actually far more closely tied to their local moral narrative and their perceived distance from existential threats.  Their values don't come from an expectancy of a long life.And your third point is absurd.  There is no class war between the 'rich' and the 'poor.'  There is tension and there is a certain hostility amongst the poor toward the rich but it is not a war.  War is acts of agression.  The rich commonly are generally just apathetic toward the poor.  The poor are aggressive to the rich but, at least in the developed world, not actively so for the time being.You are expecting people to become less selfish because they will have longer lives to look forward to.  There is nothing to suggest they would.  In fact, it's just as possible people would be more selfish because they are afraid of not being set up for their later life.

author: @IngemarKenyatta
processed_text: +finfan7 You should examine war and conflict in human history. We are in a period of unprecedented peace (despite what antiwar campaigners would have you believe). I would never deny it is speculative. Wildly? Not sure what you mean by that? The hypothesis isn't so much about not fearing death but not valuing (a short) life. There is a difference. And my larger point is that there are many varied aspects to hierarchy to examine. None of these things are being broached. Your response might suggest that you also see no relevance? Is that correct to say?

author: @kasuha
processed_text: I'm a big fan of thorium nuclear energy but there are few things that upset me about it being repeated over and over again which are simply not true.One is the claim that it will all will work atmospherhic pressure. It won't. Nuclear reaction does not care about pressure (unless we talk pressures inside an exploding atomic bomb), the only reason why current reactors use high pressure is because nuclear fuel rods are directly warming water, generating high pressure steam to power the turbine. The same is true for molten salt reactor because you always need that heat exchanger where your molten salt will be in close proximity with high pressure water/steam powering the turbine, including all the danger of steam explosion driving the radioactive material out. The more you immerse the core into the water the less heat you lose due to thermal conductivity somewhere else so I'm pretty sure industrial thorium reactors will use high pressure chambers very similar to ones used now in solid fuel reactors.And the second claim is that molten salt reactors are inherently safer because the salt is molten all the time in them. That's like claiming that overclocked CPU is inherently more reliable than non-overclocked. The safety mechanism driving the overheated molten salt into safe place is pretty much the same as protection in case of reactor meltdown in current reactors and it comes with pretty much the same problems. It may be safer than a solid-fuel reactor without meltdown protection but nobody will let you run such a reactor today.Besides, fluorine is very reactive element and thorium is not exactly the element it makes strongest bonds with, so corrosion of the reactor containment is going to be much larger issue in LFTR than in current solid fuel reactors.None of these are of course an issue with experimental reactors running at low power for a few months, but that's not the reason why we should be lied about them.Even with that all taken into account I still believe thorium is the fuel of the future.

author: @brightmal
processed_text: kasuha I believe much of the thinking going forward is focused on Supercritical CO2 and a gas turbine, and the CO2 would take the heat from a secondary loop with no fuel in the salt. So the parts that are dealing with high pressure are not also dealing with radioactivity.

author: @kasuha
processed_text: Mark Love Supercritical CO2 is nasty stuff and requires high temperatures and pressures just to exist. Also turbines run on pressure difference - the higher pressure difference (meaning the higher starting pressure and the lower ending pressure), the more efficient the turbine is.But whatever the heat transfer method, LFTR has simply no advantages against solid fuel reactors. Temperatures and technologies available are the same for both.

author: @nathansmith8157
processed_text: kasuha I don't think you have a firm understanding of the actualities beneath your concerns.  We aren't worried about containing the high pressure gases because they don't contain any radioactive isotopes, and their release won't lead to a meltdown.  Also we're constantly trying to keep the reactor hot in a LFTR instead of cool in a LWR using solid fuels.  Solid fueled requires you need to cool down, Liquid Fuel reactors you have to keep hot.  If wouldn't be too condescending I'd link Grover doing his near and far routine.

author: @kasuha
processed_text: Nathan Smith I don't quite understand in what way do your arguments counter mine.I don't see any reason why would high pressure gases in modern solid fuel reactors have to contain any more radioactive materials than high pressure gases in thorium reactors. Perhaps you have any details?From my point of view it's just water or other suitable medium flowing around metal pipes containing radioactive material and it's completely irrelevant whether that material is circulating or just sitting there. In both cases there's plenty of radioactive elements inside them if they become damaged.Whether you're keeping the reactor hot or cool is also irrelevant. In both cases you're keeping it at working temperature. From the safety point of view I don't consider higher temperature (in LFTR) safer. Yes, self-regulation of molten salt by thermal expansion is one added safety point but there are other points countering that, too.Even in solid fuel reactors, meltdown is designed and controlled process. It certainly should be avoided as it is not part of production cycle but it is designed to produce heap of molten radioactive material sufficiently diluted to prevent any chain reaction which is then drained to a special container where it can sit and cool down. Sounds perfectly the same as for LFTR to me.And you did not address my statement about Fluorine from used salts having good potential to corrode whatever containment is used to hold the salt.

author: @nathansmith8157
processed_text: The water that is used as coolant comes into direct contact with the fuel rods, inevitably transferring certain radioactive products into itself, most likely the gases like Xenon, if there is a rapid loss of pressure the water vapourises immediately to steam and expanding by 4000%, and gaseous radioactive isotopes escape along with it.That's why they build containment vessles is to contain the gaseous radioactive elements in the event of pressure loss.  The high pressure elements in a MSR do not come in direct contact with the coolant so there is no chance of transfer for the gaseous radioactive isotopes (which are siphoned off as a part of normal operation of most MSR designs) thus in the event of a pressure loss it's just steam, and should there be a leak in the MSR cooling system the gas products don't expand by 4000%.

author: @ljung4ever1
processed_text: I think you have to see the difference between descriptive and normative parts of the presentation! Greene argues that the crucial ingredient that enables good cooperation is altruism. The largest treat to successful group cooperation (and thus survival) is "free-riders", people who take more than they give. According to Greene, morality is simply nature's way of dealing with the "free-rider" problem, and that is a descriptive statement, not a normative one. Selfishness might be bad for cooperation, but since it is a descriptive argument, it does not follow that selfishness is immoral.

author: @geniusofmozart
processed_text: Owen Doyle He arrives at this conclusion because there's no rational justification for putting one's own interests above those of other people's. Each person's preferences are just as real and valid to them as yours are to you, so any objective conception of morality will recognise this. (Ironically, Rand's "objectivism" is actually the most subjective view one can take of morality.) Thus, if we are to try to satisfy our own preferences, increase our own happiness and reduce our own suffering, we must do the same for others. I would push the man because we each have to make moral decisions based our our circumstances. We can know what is moral, as explained above, and the fact that uncertainty often exists as to what yields the best result is irrelevant: we can calculate the expected value, or expected utility, of taking an action. The world's worst atrocities were often perpetrated by people who thought they had good intentions, which is precisely why consequentialism, and, specifically, utilitarianism does not take intentions into account. If those who had committed these atrocities had thought about whether they are maximising happiness impartially, they would have answered no, and so they wouldn't have committed those atrocities. Or, if they did, it's precisely because they didn't take a utilitarian viewpoint, not because they did.

author: @lavonnambrecht9630
processed_text: Hi Richard,  You make a valid argument and I think I understand why you make it.  It is very hard to imagine someone that has done something one sees as very negative being turned around to want to spread positivity.All humans are on a journey of their own.  Sometimes the journey has ugly detours one chooses to take.  Sometimes it is not our choice but it is our reality.  I might even say our journeys all have ugly detours. I know mine has. I found that the ugliness is sometimes a lesson we must learn before we can move forward.  It might take that ugliness to teach us that is not the way we want to be now.  Maybe we just grow out of it like a stage we went through as children or young adults.  Our present is who we are now.  Our past is what we did in the past.  It doesn't define who we are now. It is what we were doing before we knew about how to live better lives.  I know very little of who Russell was in his past, so I don't have to get through that particular package of negativity to hear what he is saying.I have known about most of what he is passing on to others now for a long time.  I believe what he is trying to share is valuable for every human being on our planet.  Perhaps the journey he was on allowed him to share his discovery with people who would not have learned it from anyone else. Can you imagine a bunch of rappers sitting down with the Dali Lama to hear this message?  It's pretty funny now that I see it in my mind.
