processed_text: The elephant in the room isn't Climate Change. That's a topic that is out in the open and spoken about all the time by almost everyone. The elephant in the room is the root cause of Climate Change, something that nobody ever talks about - Human overpopulation. If we could tackle that problem through legislated human cap and trade, subsidies, HOV lanes for childless people, etc., we wouldn't have a child asking, "Mommy, is a rainforest being destroyed so I can eat my hamburger?" The question he or she should be asking is, "Mommy, why did you bring me into a planet being destroyed by human overpopulation?" That's the real question.

author: @InfoSopher
processed_text: +Patricia Leary This may not be what you would want to hear, but some people use way more resources than others.Just think about it. It is obvious, that a self-sustaining farmer in a third world country, who's only producing for self use, does not have a car, has never been near an airplane, has never bought food from the other side of the world, doesn't have to heat his house (because it's near the equator), and doesn't buy a lot of cheap plastic or electronic goods will not have the same greenhouse gas emissions as an average citizen in Europe or the US, where all these things are more or less normal to do and have.If you are interested in some actual numbers on the topic, just google something like "greenhouse gas emissions per capita". The short story here is, that some regions in the world produce 10x, 20x or even 50x more than others.But the real story is even a bit more complicated.First, some of these statistics include emissions from vegetation. So if a country burns a lot of it's forests, in order to get agricultural land, its per capita emissions will rise accordingly.Another aspect that often is missing in those sort of statistics is that some countries produce a lot for export. So for example the Chinese have a large industry base that's basically producing goods for US, EU, etc consumption. Chinese domestic consumption is still very low. So is it fair, if those factories contribute to Chinese emissions in those sort of statistics?Or what about the Amazon rainforest, and the bovine and soya agriculture that has been built there for export. Should that count as Brazilian emissions, if the real consumers are mostly not Brazilian?And some of those stats are even based on weak assumptions. Up until recently, the CO2 emissions of a type of coal that's widely used in China had been overestimated. Which means that a lot of the statistics on Chinese emissions of the last few years were a few percent too high.As you can see, the details matter a great deal.Have a nice day.

author: @InfoSopher
processed_text: +perliva What do you mean by "we"? You are probably talking about humans, because you wrote "like we did for the last million years". Sure, humans might survive for a while. But our modern civilization is not millions of years old. As a matter of fact, most of it is less than 200 years old. And some argue, that most of it is still in creation. What we have is very new. We still need to learn how to make it last.Let me ask you this: When you drive on a road, do you care about what is ahead? I do, because it is much cheaper to prevent a disaster than to clean up afterwards. Besides, I can't clean up my own remains very well I think. ;)And what do you do on a misty day with low visibility? Do you slow down, or do you become another statistic?Climate change is much like that. It is about how we deal with uncertainty. Because it is true, we haven't fully understood everything about it yet. The models of how it works are not perfect. Every serious scientist will tell you that. But does that mean that we shouldn't act? Can these models ever be perfect? When is good enough, good enough?While we have not understood everything, we do know parts of it. The greenhouse gas effect of certain gasses for example has been discovered over 150 years ago. So we do know that very well. We know where the brakes, or at least some them, are.If you think the Syrian crisis is a problem, with maybe 10 million refugees, think about what could happen from climate change in 50-200 years. We have at least 4 big problems: 1. Most larger cities (3/4) are at the ocean. So they're gonna be under water, should the ice of Antarctica ever melt. We don't need that. 2. Extreme weather events, like long droughts, become more likely. Many people could die from starvation or migrate because of that. 3. Europe has a radiator that keeps it warm, called the Gulf Stream. Basically a particular pattern of water movements in the ocean. If that stops working, or get's changed in a significant way, Europe has a big problem. And 4. there are several major countries that get their water from the Himalayas, including China, India, etc. Half of the worlds population. The glaciers on those mountains are a natural buffer for water. They grow in the winter, and melt in the summer, giving necessary water to the rivers that run through those countries. I've just done some reading on this myself, and it seem like those glaciers are receding fast. And honestly, I'm most worried about that. Because if the people that rely on that water don't get what they need to survive, they will have to move somewhere else. And that effort could cause instability, which could cause the collapse of the current global economic system. And even if that doesn't occur,  it would still take up a lot of resources that could be spent on better things than cleaning up after the fact.Anyway. In the end you can only find out what makes sense to you by your self. And you can only do that by listening to the arguments that are brought forward and by thinking about them. So, since you seem to speak German, which I gather from the videos you have on your channel, I recommend to you "Der Klimawandel" by Rahmstorf and Schellnhuber. It's a very small book that gives you a good overview of the essentials. The best book I know on the subject.Have a nice day. :)

author: @normalizedinsanity4873
processed_text: I have done Marxist political economy and Marx identified this in 1850...Rate of Profit“Rate of profit” is a term introduced by Marx in Volume III of Capital for the ratio of profit to total capital invested in a given cycle of reproduction, or the proportion of value in any given commodity which constitutes profit for the capitalist.In bourgeois economics, “rate of profit” means the proportion of the total capital invested accruing to the capitalist as profit per annum.For a given period of circulation, or cycle of reproduction, the two definitions are equivalent. The circulation time of capital is the time that elapses between a capitalist making an initial investment and when the products are sold and the original capital plus a profit are recovered. This cycle of reproduction is a major factor in the development of capitalism, and much of Volume II of Capital is concerned with circulation of capital and the problems of Realisation.Keeping in mind the distinction between the Marxist and conventional uses of the term “rate of profit”, the following issues are of importance.Surplus Value and ProfitIf a certain quantity of constant and variable capital are invested in a productive process, then at the end of a cycle of reproduction these values will have renewed themselves, but in addition, if the labour power of the employees has used to at least the social average of usefulness, there will a surplus-value.Marx expresses this symbolically: c + v -> c + v + s, where c is the constant capital, vthe variable capital (wages) and s is the surplus value, and the value of every product can be seen as composed of these parts.On the basis of this conception, the rate of profit for the individual capitalist who got into the game of profiteering by investing (c + v) at the beginning of the cycle of reproduction, makes a ‘profit’ of s and therefore the rate of profit is s/(c + v). The individual capitalist is unlikely to see this surplus value in its entirety however, for the landlord, the state, the bank and everyone else will all demand a cut of this surplus: the productive worker must maintain not only “their own” capitalist, but all manner of hangers-on as well.This rate of profit, s/(c + v), which is the ratio which affects the individual unit of capital, is different from the rate of surplus value, s/v.The rate of surplus value expresses the proportion of unpaid labour that workers donate to the capitalist (s) over to the necessary labour time, v, that the workers spend reproducing their own needs, and is paid as wages, or variable capital.Tendency of Rate of Profit to FallMarx believed that there was an historic tendency for the rate of profit to fall as a result of the growing socialisation and complexity of the labour process, and the growing productivity of labour. Each capitalist employs less labour and spends more on machinery and materials to produce the same value. Marx characterised this process as an increasing “organic composition of capital”. Since employing workers is the only source of profit, Marx believed that the rate of profit would fall.The tendency of the rate of profit to fall, Marx believed is one of the main contributors to the historic crisis of capitalism.

processed_text: Hi guys, I have to say that I have enjoyed reading this book and think it settles many strong ideas that will bring down the current economic system to its knees.However, as a reader, I wanna warn others that in Chapter 14, there is a piece of misinformation regarding Bitcoin creation. author: @LordTomnoddy
processed_text: Reviewing this vid serves only to reinforce the previous impression I had of (no point in being coy) the covert "introgression" (ha-ha-ha!) into the presentation of an unhealthy dollop of political correctness. Especially now I've seen earlier, very similar presentations by Paabo in which some of the figures quoted are somewhat different. Notably, in a 2011 talk, he uses almost the same diagram as is shown here from 22:03 mins; and to illustrate much the same point--   --except then the figure for Neanderthal contribution to modern non-African genomes is given as C2.5%. Significantly higher than the 1 - 2% shown on the diagram in the more recent presentation.Yet afaik, no research suggesting a downward revision in the assessment has been conducted or released in the peer reviewed literature in intervening period. How the Neanderthal contribution to modern non-African genomes seems to have almost halved, apparently quite spontaneously and in just three years is perhaps, then, something of a mystery.While moreover, an elementary calculation based on the figures given earlier in both presentations relating to the comparative incidence of individual base pair matches between Neanderthal, and African and non-African genomes show a consistent C9% greater incidence of non-African matches.

processed_text: Jennifer Fama : The LGBT movement is not ideological. It is a human rights and civil rights movement. Sexual orientation and gender identity are accidents of birth, just like skin colour, and ethnic origin. Those are things you don't decide upon; they are not a belief or choice. The so-called main stream definitions are wrong. We clung on to them for so long because simplicity is attractive, especially when it is binary. But no matter how much easier to believe the simpler definitions may be, that doesn't make them true. And forcing real people to fit those definitions is barbaric. Gays having to pretend to be straight out of fear of being discriminated or killed ... that's not a life. The same is true for trans people: gender identity sometimes doesn't align with assigned sex at birth. But condemning them to a life of self-denial, or having them beaten, killed, and driven to suicide, just so that simplicity of definition may reign over reality ... is a crime against humanity.

author: @umayusu
processed_text: Great talk that puts into words the anxious feeling I always get when I watch the news: a sense of confused meaningless in a mass of information that should (in most cases) have real importance in our lives. I love the idea that information should be contextualised and analysed thematically, with the implications/ lessons in our own lives explored, and with suggestions for possible action. But I feel that having more bias in the news would add to the confusion and lack of orientation that we experience already. I think news should be told in the words of those involved, or in photography/ film. Then, the biases are of those involved in the situations, the information can be contextualised better, and there'll be at least some extent of representation.Aljazeera's 'Witness' and VICE documentaries are quite good in this respect, although not perfect of course. But they instil curiosity and a sense of importance about the subject matter. Point is, I think social media will help the voices of those involved in events be heard better, to enable us to understand the reality, rather than the intrigues and technicalities that take up air time. Palestine is a key example. A lot more people have become attuned to the reality of the apartheid there because more voices from those involved are coming through in social media. But of course, these voices can be flooded with mindless droll. I need to go to bed.

author: @slaphaddalztick
processed_text: There is no CO2 problem. Current levels at 385 ppm are close to the lowest in the history of this planet. below 200ppm, and we'd all be dead. Below 500, and plants die off dramatically. CO2 is great for life on earth, plants love it, which is why CO2 levels in Greenhouses are 1000ppm. We need more CO2, not less. Most of the people commenting on this video seem to think that CO2 is a poison, when it is a necessity for life on earth. Nor is CO2 a big player when it comes to Greenhouse gases. Water vapour accounts for 95% of all greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, with CO2 accounting for just 3.6%, of which the human contribution is just 0.117%, completely insignificant and unlikely to have any but the barest minimal effect on the climate. Atmospheric levels of CO2 are indeed rising today, but there has been no global warming now for 18 years. You global warming junkies so want the world to warm that you can scream ' CO2 CO2' as loud as you can at every opportunity, but however loud you shout, nature will just do what it has always done, the climate will change, ice ages will come and go, and this will carry on long after humans have disappeared from the face of the earth.

author: @kimweaver3323
processed_text: +Tim Fouraker   Fool.  Whenever I see the alleged " no warming for some period" canard, I know I am dealing with a buffoon or a shill.  There has been a LOT of heating....and cooling....on a year to year basis for the last 18 years.  The idiotic idea that drawing a line between one data point and another somehow determines a trend is just as dumb as you can get.  So, try this.  You are starting your line at 1997-1998, a freakishly hot year, and ends up today.  The line was nearly flat when you guys were drawing it to end at 2013.  But when drawn to today, it shows an increase.  Now try this.  Since 2000 is within your 18 year time frame, draw a line from the average global temperature from 2000 to today.  It is a steeply rising line, because 2000 was an unusually cool year.  So, if you use this idiotic technique that you are proposing, then there has been moderate heating during the last 18 years, or there has been severe heating in the last 16 years.  Neither is valid.  The trend line, smoothing the extremes both high and low, show a moderate heating for decades and continuing into the future.  So Timmy, you are dismissed.  Go get some edumakashun.

author: @khuix
processed_text: +TheCobalt100 I don't really think his arguments are that convincing and here's why:1. The biggest tell is that he's using Newtonian physics to describe a relativistic event. We already know Newtonian physics is an approximation for relativity. It's not accurate at all for events happening on a much larger scale. His hurricane analogy, while accurate in some sense, doesn't really disprove black holes.2. He asserts that all black holes have to rotate. In his argument, all black holes can only exist in spiral galaxies which isn't true either. The rotational force of spiral galaxies isn't necessarily caused by a black hole. All matter have an attractive force between one another. If you ever threw 2 magnets in parallel and close enough together, they'll maintain their forward velocity but start spiraling around one another. In this same way, stars and other matter in space swirl around each other in spiral galaxies.3. You also have to realize this guy literally says he's just taken "some" astronomy classes in college. Based on his age, you can surmise the curriculum taught while he was learning probably wasn't the most recent. Even if we gave him the benefit of the doubt and said he just finished the courses, black holes are very complicated physical phenomenons that are studied in depth for years. I doubt he has the necessary credentials to even talk about it let alone claim its non-existence.

author: @SeymourSunshine
processed_text: Dark energy is the energy of a vacuum. It isn't immediately obvious that a vacuum contains energy until you consider the complex components of the solution to quadratic line integral of the 9-dimensional Fermi equation written as a tensor.Elementary analysis of the equation leads to several interesting real and unreal solutions. When the trivial solutions are excluded and the RMS value of the negative solutions is added to the sum over all i the result is, of course, a natural non-integer.The inescapable conclusion is, therefore, that the origin of dark energy is the interaction at the boundary layer of the universal hadron density and the tachyon vector normalised at the Schwarzkopf limit.A back-of-an-envelope calculation leads to the rough result of 80% which is very close to the observed value.Further calculations should lead to a more accurate value once we can find a larger envelope.

author: @ScotchmanGass
processed_text: This company is a farce. I am a Journeyman Railroad safety inspector who began working for Amazon in California back in 2013. I turned down a "lead associate" position as I do not believe in starting out as a boss; one must work upward to earn it. In orientation and at "stand-up" meetings they preach Safety, Quality and then Speed, however, the bosses get you alone and say "forgot what you just heard, Quick, Fast, Speed is the key. Therefore, safety and quality mean nothing to this company. In fact, this company is a Chinese concept operating in the USA. My safety requests were ignored by their maintenance department who supplied us with cheap Chinese step stools in which Amazon removed the wheels, thus making the stool more than 40% weaker. Therefore, people put their feet right through them and they were injured. When I began to be harassed by a company lead, I sent an E-mail to my manager to inform him, which was ignored for weeks. I noticed that my department (ICQA) was creating errors and assigning those errors to other people, I reported this. I was made to completely understand that they use this method as a "filter" to wrongfully terminate employees they don't want. On one particular night in the wee hours of the morning Amazon allowed contractors to perform illegal welding ( no dust suction, fans or open windows to ventilate as they were still building this facility while we were working in it) in the building which caused a thick fume of welding vapor and gases to overwhelm the entire workforce (including me) in their A-Mod. People ran out choking, coughing, complaining of a terrible headache and appeared as if ready to vomit. My boss told me to keep working! I went to their Amcare station and pleaded with them to help as this is a very serious Cal-OSHA violation. The company began to retaliate against me, denying any excuse for any absence which is illegal as you cannot punish people for merely being ill. I was very sick with pneumonia for weeks and had to go to the Emergency room at the hospital; my medical proof of my extensive treatments was rejected. I was told, "too bad you don't qualify for the FLP (family leave program) as I had not been there for a year or more. However, my co-worker hired the same day I was, had been granted permission to the program even though it was not she who was ill, it was her very old mother. She was allowed to miss more than two months worth of work with no penalty, or loss of PTO (paid time off) or UPT (unpaid time off) and she thought it was funny and bragged about it. The General Manager is a carpetbagger from England and cares nothing for the USA. I kept a time, dated employment journal (as always) which I E-mailed to their management and informed as to my issues. I also demanded to speak with the GM who would only speak with me at around three AM. I was denied a witness and I was informed that he would "take care of it" and I was fired the next day.Amazon deleted all of my time cards, so I could not prove that they did not pay me for the last three days I worked. I was led to a dark room by one person from human resources and someone I had never before met; they only spoke in barely audible whispers (out of fear that I was recording them) I was handed a credit card (for final payment which was not accurate) with no breakdown of my payment. I was the highest performer in my department (ICQA) achieving a perfect score several times and I had no negative performance reviews which totaled more than twenty; Amazon erased them all and placed two negative reviews (devoid of my signature) in their place. Finally, I demanded to view and record my employee file to which they refused (this is illegal as anyone has a right to view their file) and told me it would have to be subpoenaed. I was not acting as a whistle-blower, or I would have informed to OSHA, but I did not; I tried to help this bald-headed traitor to the American concept. Amazon sucks!

author: @TheEpicmonday
processed_text: Interesting talk. But it is interesting to notice how the entire concept of strategy seems to be based on the notion of win-lose-games. As in games where you have an opponent ( or even "enemy" to use the warlanguage ) and where the purpose is assumed to "beat" this opponent. As he mentioned in warfare in MOST cases the battles are very prolonged and in fact both parties lose. Meaning : The win-lose narrative does not seem to actually work in practice. Because of this it is strange that not more was said about the strategy for win-win games. Here of course you avoid the entire problem of someone trying to frustrate you and prevent your strategy from working. In win-win games there is even an incentive for transparent cooperation and mutual learning which is not possible in a win-lose scenario. Is win-win strategy a neglected and overlooked area in this research?

author: @a_little_bit_of_wisdom
processed_text: Good show. An Oxford don speaks to a naive, cocooned Silicon Valley audience. He's got lots of knowledge, but offers limited advice. He's old school, from an old country, wearing a navy suit and tie.  Google employees who introduce and question Freedman wear t-shirts. They don't appear to have read his book, but remain cocky.Freedman has a message. It's best expressed by his Eisenhower quote. "Plans are worthless, but planning is essential." Strategic plans rarely pan out as expected. People love narratives, and those who succeed cast their success as a series of strategic steps. Most often close examination finds these steps were solutions to immanent problems, not stages of a strategy driven journey.This doesn't sit well with Google's analytic programmers. Check the source code of this page, and there's certainly a link that reports my behavior to them. They package and sell this data to advertisers, claiming it predicts market behavior. Being lectured on the limits of repeated "games," on unpredictable randomness, tells them Google's users may not respond as they're expected.Freedman studies war and business, but his advice is mostly for business people, not warriors. This talk's audience is small, and probably unrepresentative. Otherwise Google has a myopic, one-track company culture.

author: @TheAbsorbant
processed_text: Everyone's entitled to their opinion, I guess.

author: @barrywonderdog
processed_text: TheAbsorbant Logically, the existence of the more dynamic sounding Guitar Hero mix suggests this might be as much down to mastering as it is to engineering.Rather than blaming the engineer, we should be pointing the finger at a system that disallows an engineer from practicing his or her craft fully. The most knowledgable engineer on the planet is still ultimately dictated to by the artist and A&R, because they are the engineer's clients. This has created the bizarre situation where 'the customer knows best' even when the customer ends up wrecking the end result for their customers; the listeners and fans.It must be uniquely frustrating as an engineer to submit a mix to a band, knowing that their response can be translated as, "we'd like you to ruin it, or we'll ruin you." But, unless we move back to hiring an expert to be an expert, instead of hiring an expert to acquiesce expertly to the client's wishes, this will continue. And, sadly, that isn't going to happen.

author: @TheAbsorbant
processed_text: The mastering engineer in question made an official statement when the criticism started, that the mix sounded like this when he got it.Sure, everything you're saying is true, but Rick Rubin and Andrew Scheps have been championing the distorted, over saturated, brickwalled sound for years. Rick Rubin started this even as early as Red Hot Chili Peppers' "Californication" and it's only gotten worse.Sheps says in this talk that he mixes too hot on purpose. Meanwhile, Metallica have stated that they were reviewing the mixes in dressing room tents at summer festivals. They probably didn't hear what the final mixes sounded like until the CDs were pressed and nothing could be done about it.

author: @barrywonderdog
processed_text: TheAbsorbant Agreed, but I'm not sure whether the desire to mix hot comes from the engineer, or from pressure placed on engineering from all sides. Rick Rubin has been championing hot mixes for years, but there's also that bootlegged early mix of Californication (possibly a pre-release candidate) that is mixed a lot less hot. Presumably Rubin was involved in the creation of that, too. I think the album was mixed sensibly at first, then mixed and mastered hot, and Rubin prefers to take the credit for that rather than look like he was shouted down. Unfortunately, Californication went on to be RHCP's biggest seller, and more artists and A&R people start demanding similar.I think these guys have been backed into a corner (partly of their own making). Now, no one wants their mix thrown back at them by the artist saying "what are we, a jazz combo?" so they mix hot, because that's what the client wants from them. The big question is would they mix hot if the recording itself rather than the client was uppermost in their thoughts?

author: @RealHomeRecording
processed_text: +Jake E Hobbs Famous audio engineer Bob Clearmountain disagrees with you. And so do I."Clearmountain, who now works out of Mix This! in Pacific Palisades, says that when he heard the vinyl test pressings of the albums he'd worked on in the studio, he always felt the same way: depressed."I'd just listen and go: 'Jesus, after all that work, that's all I get?' It was sort of a percentage of what we did in the studio," he says. "All that work and trying to make everything sound so good, and the vinyl just wasn't as good."Not only did records provide only a sliver of what he'd done in the studio but they also came with plenty of sounds that hadn't been there in the first place: ticks and pops."If you're a musician like Bob and I," Ludwig says, "and you get to do a mix and you listen to it and you love the way it sounds, and then it's transferred to vinyl and suddenly it's got noise and ticks and pops, for me that's an extremely unmusical event."Read more by Googling Do CDs Sound Better than Vinyl? Pay special attention to the fact that he said early digital, thanks to conversion technologies, wasn't great. The bottom line? From frequency response to dynamic range and distortion, digital beats vinyl.

author: @MrDonnyAir
processed_text: +Jonathan Laird I'd rather listen to a mix with a nicely preserved dynamic range any day, than listen to an uber-limited over-squashed mix in favor of "LOUD". I hear some of these mastered mixes, with a DR of -4 to -2 and to me it's just noise. The musical part has all been wiped out.  The last album I mixed, I adhered to the LUFS standard and the mastering engineer who I sent it to emailed me a "thank you" note.  LOL  In the end, the mastered album had an RMS/DR of around -14 to -12, and it was wonderful to listen to sonically.

author: @MrDonnyAir
processed_text: DR is, thankfully, coming back. The last project I mixed had a DR of 12db, and that was AFTER mastering... and NO ONE has complained.  Too the contrary, the artist and I are getting compliments as to how nice the mixes sound. And, Hi Res waves are always going to be the best bet. We all know this. Unfortunately, with the MP3, it's the best of the devils available to us for convenient upload and online distribution at this time. I would encourage those who do digital downloads to choose a FLAC format, if they are given the choice and if their media player supports it.

author: @timg3830
processed_text: FauxReal when Jonathan is referring to 4db, what he's referring to is 4db of compression, or a 4db reduction in the peak levels of the signal.I disagree hyperliteBo about the RCHP record, I think it sounds fantastic. and I think bitrate and sample rates do matter, when you are dealing with digital files and streaming. also remember that the compression added in mixing is only one stage in multiple stages of compression before the actual product is released to the general public. I will however, agree with you on the fact that there is nothing wrong with CD quality, as I usually track in 44.1khz, albeit I'm working in 24 bit mode (such is the way with the modern DAW), and I do sometimes have a hard time hearing the difference between 96 and 44.1 when I'm working in the studio

author: @FastFoodLifers1
processed_text: What I loved about 3rd (especially 3.5, the 'hot fix patch' lol) was that anyone could be anything.However, my best enjoyment in 2nd Edition was playing a Rogue... that wasn't a Rogue.  I was a Run Away Wizard (from the Red Isles) and my plan was to not use Wizardry so I would be harder to find by those my Parents sent for me.  So... I told everyone I was a Rogue.Such intense moments trying to keep my cover.  Skulking about acting like I'm looking for Traps, when I wouldn't know a Trap even after it killed me.  My first Locked Picked for Treasure (it wasn't locked, but no one knew it... myself included).The only distraction was a Meta-Gamer who kept worrying about my Character instead of his "Hey, you're a Rogue... shouldn't you be doing this?  Hey, do this.  Do that.  Let me see your Character Sheet."  That was the only thing that came close to ruining the awesomeness of the adventure.I worked harder crafting his Back Story and getting his details (Handem Swyndel) than I had on anyone ever before, poured my soul into that attempt.So I can always thank 2nd Edition for how things were Restricted, and how that became my Challenge.LOL!  "You see a Chest.  It looks locked."  Hey guys, we need to be safe... I need you guys checking the other corners of this room for Traps, Secret Doors, things like that.  Don't worry, I'll be coming around and checking what you find."  Hmm, did they buy that?  While they aren't looking, what's the incantation for 'Knock' again?  Gotta be quiet, can't let them see me gesture. Loved it.But from a Rules and Lay Out point, 3.5 was all me.  But then they went HEAVY into Forgotten Realms, and THAT is right up my alley.I'll have to look into 5 again, but it just seems so much like Warhammer RPG.

processed_text: ***** Oh yeah sure, children being born into poverty, suffering from horrific diseases, being born with HIV, coming into this world with birth defects.... Life was not created by some cosmic author planning out specific events for the creatures that have evolved on our planet. Language, abstract thought, and philosophical speculation are all products of natural evolution. Simply because there has been a concept of a soul stretching back to pre-socratic greek philosophers does not at all validate this idea that the soul even exists or rather it was designed specifically for the learning of lessons.This "soul" did not have any sort of consciousness before embodiment. processed_text: Dennett is wrong that neuroscientists telling people that they don't have free will is the same as the surgeon telling the patient that they now control his decisions.The surgeon is taking on the responsibility of the patient's decisions, but no one is taking on that responsibility in the case of the neuroscientists using determinism to refute free will. The physical laws aren't conscious intelligent agents that care about you. You still have to take care of yourself even when you know the physical laws are controlling you. You don't have access to all the physical mechanics happening within and around you, so knowing you're being controlled by those mechanics should mean nothing to your decision making.It's an enormous fallacy to think that being controlled by physical laws means that you should give in to primal desires and emotions and disregard all responsibilities and consequences. As I have stated, nothing changes when you know you are controlled by physical laws because you lack knowledge of those processes and what they will bring. You have no choice but to continue on the presumption of free will even though it may not exist in an absolute sense. It's a useful illusion much like the illusion of color or cuteness.

author: @soundworksdeejay
processed_text: Great work, Mr. Frankel.  Really enjoyed your Google video. My great-great grandfather, ie, Luther Thomas Martin Plummer was Rachel (Parker's) husband.  Rachel Plummer  & Cynthia Ann Parker were 1'st cousins.  James Pratt Plummer was Luther & Rachel Plummer's son and all 3 along with Cynthia Ann's brother (John) and a Mrs. Elizabeth Kellogg were captured by the Commanche' & Kiowas on May 19, 1836; that is, 2 months after the Alamo fell and 1 month after General Sam Houston & his Texas army defeated Santa Anna at the Battle of San  Jacinto.     Before I forget here is my Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/SoundworkS.DeeJayBack To Subject.......As a Texas Centennial (1936) and President Roosevelt CCC project my late father (James Garland Plummer)  helped in the reconstruction of the original Fort Parker & on its original site.  It's a tourist destination today located between Mexia & Groesbeck, Texas.  Below is a link to a side story or a bit of "soap opera" (if you will)  that took place between "Uncle James" Parker's  son-in-law and my great-great grandfather, Luther Thomas Martin Plummer.   Even General Sam Houston played a role with his response letter to my great-great grandfather of which the details of the incident can be found in late author Frank X. Tolbert's book "An Informal History of Texas."  Click the below link and then about half way down the page look for this in bold letters: A NON-REVISED HISTORY UPDATE ABOUT THE REVEREND JAMES PARKER  Here's the link and....enjoy!     http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_Parker_massacre#James_W._Parker

author: @MendicantBias1
processed_text: The citizen-soldier is defined by their awareness of politics and domestic concerns in relation to the act of war. The modern US military has used the excuse of professional detachment from politics as license to fully devote themselves to promotion, risk mitigation, and expansion of their respective branches inside the expanding DoD budget. We are in this mess today because all parties involved in the making of war have given moral and ethical responsibility to someone else. Where the military commits a war crime it is the fault of the politicians who sent them, and where the elected leaders take a nation to war unjustly and without regard for our well being or prosperity they pass the buck to hindsight, fog and friction of war, and just plain old ignorance. When will someone take responsibility? It is the citizen-soldier who both respects civilian authority and simultaneously takes politics into consideration when preparing the machines of war for their wicked purposes. War is evil, albeit necessary for the survival of a nation against hostile aggression. We have divorced ourselves as a nation from all the consequences of war. Now all we need to do is watch the clock and wonder when our foreign policy will come home to roost.

processed_text: 44:04 Regarding women being givers in close relationships and men being givers to strangers, the reason is that women, in general, are governed by stage-3 morality ("good girl" morality or ethics of care) but men can go up to stage-6 (universal ethics or ethics of justice). Stage-3 morality is selfish in the sense that you don't want to waste your good behavior on someone (e.g., a stranger) who will not have a chance to repay the behavior in future; in essence, there is an expectation of a return/reward (at least psychological, like respect) for good behavior.

processed_text: Watching Google talks reveals a lot about the company's "culture". It's very self-focused - dozens of examples get shown, all from Google's workspace. Stephen's story about the Whale Song blackout scene reminds me of a time I did pretty much the exact same thing!It was during a family vacation, we were going on a road trip and we had to take two cars to fit everyone and our stuff. As this was back before cell phones became common products, we bought walkie talkies so we could communicate between cars. We treated the walkie talkies like toys for most of the trip, simply telling jokes back and forth to one another, so I was trying to think of a way of One Upping my sisters.So then suddenly I was struck by inspiration, picked up the walkie talkie, and in my best female radio DJ voice said:"And now for your listening pleasure, I present to you: Songs of the Whale." Then preceded to make whaling, clicking noises for a minute.Unbeknownst to me in the other car, everyone was losing their minds with laughter, and the Songs of the Whale bit turned into a running gag in family events for a long time.

author: @Matiyahu
processed_text: Jack Ripper Ontological argument is intense, especially Platniga's version. Colbert is Catholic; this must be a shocker for all the anti-Christian bigots who are also Colbert fans. OA: 1.It is a conceptual truth (or, so to speak, true by definition) that God is a being than which none greater can be imagined (that is, the greatest possible being that can be imagined).2. God exists as an idea in the mind.3. A being that exists as an idea in the mind and in reality is, other things being equal, greater than a being that exists only as an idea in the mind.4. Thus, if God exists only as an idea in the mind, then we can imagine something that is greater than God (that is, a greatest possible being that does exist).5. But we cannot imagine something that is greater than God (for it is a contradiction to suppose that we can imagine a being greater than the greatest possible being that can be imagined.)6. Therefore, God exists.

author: @tulio84z
processed_text: Matt Robinson So God exists simply because we can't imagine anything greater than God? That is pure insanity.

author: @Matiyahu
processed_text: Marco T. Zahn You're skimming over the argument without considering the logical necessity it proposes. First, notice premise 3 "A being that exists as an idea in the mind and in reality is, other things being equal, greater than a being that exists only as an idea in the mind."  The quality (or category) of "greatest possible being" requires the existence of said being. Since we could imagine something greater than an idea that only exists in the mind, whenever we speak of God as an idea in the mind we are not really speaking about God, because, "the greatest possible being" is definitively extant. So, we cannot imagine something great than God who, thus, exists by necessity.   This argument is a bit puzzling at first but has considerable strength.

author: @ltzu7734
processed_text: Marco T. Zahn It's not pure insanity though... It just seems like that. I have spent hours perplexed by it now. so yo can conceive of god, but by definition, when you conceive of god, you can't think he just exists in the mind. therefore, god must exist in reality because you must admit that god exists conceptually and you must admit that god is the highest possible being. If you are truly stubborn, and admit the obvious (god exists in the mind, e.g. this argument) but declare its in mind alone, you can then imagine a being greater than god (one thats not just in the mind). That being is more so god than the definition you used before that declaration so ipso facto what you think of is not God when you claim God is mental alone. Because you can think of a God as real, but you can't think of a God as solely imaginary, you must consider realness a neccessary attribute of God.  This unintuitive jump comes from formal logic, I think. There is a principle called the law of excluded middle which demands that the logician keep A and Not-A non-equal. God cannot both be in the mind defined as the greatest being and be unreal. God can just not exist in the mind, or it can exist in the mind and in reality at the same time, but any idea of God that is just mental is an impostor concept. Therefore, by the time a "fool" claims God is solely in the mind and agrees with Anslems definition of God, he has claimed God is real by considering God at all. If he rescinds his statement God is unreal, and any statement about God at all, there is no logical argument, or logical proof why God is real. I think its more clear to say "Anslem proved one cannot logically deny the existence of God. One can only stay agnostic or illogically deny God's existence."I wish I wouldn't have found this problem to be honest. I think its going to confuse me for a long time. It does seem to be a formal logic argument (as opposed to empirical, which would make claims of God seem more overtly right or wrong than this backwards, mind-bending, intellectual puzzle). Hopefully, If I ever go to learn e.g. Modal Logic, I will have a better understanding of this strange argument.

author: @squamish4244
processed_text: *****I only offered an ad hominem attack because Kurzweil clearly suffers from a lot of existential angst, and as one commentator put it, could be "having the most public midlife crisis in history."  Psychological distress is well known to affect one's ability to think rationally.As for an argument that is not directly concerned with Kurzweil's state of mind, I will repeat:  no one, anywhere, can agree on what a mind is, much less how to create one.  Yet Kurzweil has not only based his entire Singularity notion on it, he has attached a specific date to that event!  To return to Kurzweil the man again, as the concept of the Singularity cannot be separated from his domination of the public discourse on the issue, the date that he predicts just so happens to fall barely within his possible lifespan given present-day medicine (he will be 96 in 2045).  That strikes me as somewhat suspicious timing.

author: @k98killer
processed_text: Brilliant guy, but he got a few things wrong. First, neural networks have come a long way since he gave this talk. Now, LSTM networks/neural Turing machines are the major brains behind NLP. Google Translate, for example, is a series of networks that can each translate a human language into a series of vectors representing meaning, share them across a neural interface, and then translate back into a human language. Second, dinosaurs didn't go extinct: tens of thousands of them fly around to this day. Birds and mammals survived the K-T event because they were adaptable. If you look at corvids, they have language skills that far exceed that of all non-human apes; they have more advanced skills in making and using tools than most apes; and they are able to teach others in their flocks about things, perpetuating knowledge through multiple generations. Corvids have a very different brain structure without a neocortex, but their evolutionary history converged upon the same abilities. It is unfortunate that he dismissed both neural networks and non-neocortical brain structures, but he will probably change his opinions.

author: @KamilCzerski
processed_text: @Neueregel I can't agree with You: "Moore's Law", not a law anymore. CPUs are stalled at 7 nm."While it is true that due to some thermal limitations growth in processor's clock speed has almost stopped (~2003), further progress, according to Moore's law (computational power is doubled over two years) was reached by adding another cores to processor. This approach does not speed up sequential program so there is need to change paradigm for parallel programming. There are two ways: 1) multicore cpu's (2,4,6,8...) cores which support heavy threads (branching prediction etc) or 2) manycore GPU's (thousands of cores) supporting lightweight-threads (single instruction multiple data). Numerical application with high computational complexity are now mainly implemented on GPU's due to high efficiency and low cost <1000USD. 2. Our brain is very slow (for a single instruction point of view) but it's massively parallel. Artificial neural network is also a good example of program that can be parallelized.

author: @PeterFritzWalter
processed_text: The message of Lang Lang is that even if you are a lousy pianist, you should not despair for if you believe in yourself and if you have the right attitude. Please do not misunderstand me, I am not saying that Lang Lang is a lousy pianist. I am saying that he has a personal way to play, and I think that is the only way you will ever succeed in today's world of musical performance. After all, Arthur Rubinstein said this in a public interview, when being asked if he was the best pianist of his time:—No, I am not. There are many other pianists who play technically better than I do, but the public likes my way to play, and this is what counts for me.I think the same is true today for Lang Lang. Yuja Wang plays much better than him, and yet he has established a place in a niche of the classical musical repertoire. I am not a fan of his play, but I love him as a human, the way he talks, the way he teaches children, the way he is simply himself. He is a lovely person, that's what I want to say ...

author: @diebydeath
processed_text: Jason Champion It might be out of tune, but also remember that seeing as though the ukulele is such a small instrument, you have to strum rather hard to get the sound to project loudly enough, and the harder you strum the more out of tune the sound is. It's usually not out of tune enough to sound out of tune with itself, but there's a very slight difference in pitch.

author: @JasonMatthewChampion
processed_text: diebydeath Yea, good point, and I get that. This one is plugged in however. But, I imagine, because of the tuning, those nylon strings are probably stretching quite a bit.  I just bought one myself - 2 days ago - and it seems to slip quite a bit more than a steel strimg guitar.

author: @robertowen1607
processed_text: Jason Champion If you look on his headstock you will see a Snark. I will guarantee his instrument is in tune. The short stings on a uke sometimes seem off.

author: @JasonMatthewChampion
processed_text: Well, with all due respect, I don't think a Snark guarantees a tuned instrument.  Regardless, the ukulele I own, and the two my friend owns, seem to slip very easily with new strings.  I'm guessing that he has new strings.  I think they take much longer to stretch.  Plus, you may be on to something there with the short strings theory.  The intonation on ukes may be as good as they can get with their neck.  I'm not certain though.  I just know, many times when I hear someone else playing, they seem out of tune.  More so than a mandolin, a banjo, a guitar, or other instruments.  Not a big deal though, just wondering.  I certainly don't want to take away from the guy's talent.

author: @robertowen1607
processed_text: Jason Champion Of course that happens with new strings. The man is a top professional. I doubt he would perform with a newly strung instrument. My own tenor, which I play every day, barely needs to be tweeked when I take it out of the case in the morning and it holds tune beautifully while I am playing. There is nothing better than a snark for accurate tuning.

author: @deeman524
processed_text: More strings has it's benefits, but so does less, I play Both Tenor and baritone Ukulele, Guitalele, Dulcimer and Guitar, I  love the full sound of six strings but I also love the melodic sound of 3 or 4.  On fretted instruments less strings are more melodic and more strings are warmer in sound.     Pro Guitar players play ukulele on their guitars frequently without thinking about it- they play the top 4 strings as Chord Fragments for a more mellow sound, I do this too when I play in the band.    What I really love about the Uke is I can play arpeggios better and play melodies even within the rhythm easily,  playing melodies is easier and more creative when you have less strings to work with.

author: @Vortigan07
processed_text: This man is a legend! I was only 8 years old when NMTB came out so the whole thing passed me by at the time,sadly.It's funny to see how history has remembered them versus how they were viewed at the time.Hated,reviled,banned,considered as subversive and even dangerous.It's recognised now of course as one of the most important and influential albums ever recorded.The blistering punch that the songs deliver is still as strong today,this was a band with a far deeper relevance and musical aptitude than people thought.Like I said,funny how things turn out....if you're not familiar with what The Sex Pistols did in the town of Huddersfield on Christmas Day 1977  I'd strongly recommend you to look it up and see just what this "dangerous and reviled" band were really about.Then contrast that with someone who was loved by all back in 1977,one Jimmy Savile......well we now know what he was really about too! I guess the truth of all things will out in the end.I'm just pleased that The Pistols are getting their recognition here in this life rather than any of them getting one of those insincere posthumous tributes.How the music industry could do with someone like them to shake it up again!

author: @NoEcologyNoEconomy
processed_text: The 2009 Jacobson & Delucchi study says the world would need about 3.8 MILLION large wind turbines, and glosses over how much land would truly be affected. Wind power doesn't just sacrifice a few isolated regions, e.g. the carnage w/Alberta tar sands. Wind turbines are visible far and wide, and many people are stuck living among them (animals suffer untold harm). The wind zealots pretend the only land affected is where the towers touch down, which bizarrely ignores the vertical blight and total acreage webbed by towers and roads. A single wind project can loom over tens of thousands of acres, giving the whole area an industrial feel. When you see wind turbines miles away from their official sites, the tainted viewshed spreads much further. The 250,000 wind turbines already littering the planet are causing enough blight already, but neo-enviros want about 15 times that amount!

author: @andrebalsa203
processed_text: Even assuming a thorium reactor could be built that is perfectly safe (an assumption that can clearly be disputed), hard math and facts show that a thorium reactor fleet would take centuries to be deployed. The reason is summarized in two words: doubling time (or Td). This is the time it would take for a TMSR to breed enough U-233 to fuel another identical TMSR. And the answer is, in the best of cases, 52 years (in the worst case, 200 years). Remember, first, that U-233 does not exist in nature, it must be created in a breeder reactor in the first place, by breeding thorium, then processing the spent thorium to separate and remove the U-233. Second, because thorium is not fissile although it is fertile, a TMSR requires a certain quantity of U-233 to get a critical reaction started. Check here for the math: https://indico.cern.ch/event/222140/session/7/contribution/27/attachments/363090/505441/Daniel_Mathers_v2_ThEC13.pdf (that's from CERN so I assume these guys know what they are talking about).Conveniently the guys from the Thorium Alliance always forget to mention the issue of doubling time in ALL their interviews, presentations and videos...The US is the only country in the world that has any significant reserves of U-233 (the result of breeding thorium in traditional uranium-cycle reactors) and even so, these reserves would only be enough to get at most a couple of medium-sized (<500MW) reactors started in the first place. Clearly not a solution for the energy/global warming crisis and the simple reason why no country in the world has ever undertaken further work on thorium reactors in the last 50 years (beyond some simple experiments).

author: @Orygyn
processed_text: Admittedly I'm only half-way through the talk but Joshua appears to be getting quite embarrassingly schooled by his audience. He doesn't seem to understand the technology that Google is developing or what it really means to "call up information instantly". While the smartphone and other wearables exist, the latency and the external presence of the information are just a surrogate memory and inferior to the real thing, but as the technology continues to get smaller, you'll get to the point where it's actually IN the brain. At that point it can interact with the brain's circuitry and all the world's information can not only be instantly called at any time, but it becomes a meaningful statement to say that it's part of your memory. At that point, memorising something will literally be no different to posting a piece of information onto the internet, which, given that level of sophistication, you could do via thought.

author: @MrAndrew535
processed_text: One of the most pertinent questions of our time and asked with the utmost professional courtesy.  It seemed patently and increasingly more obvious as the interview progressed that Tolle ultimately lacked the referential framework with which to process the question, let alone offer an intelligent response.  Not a lack in the man but certainly in his experience in this field of existential evolution.I have little doubt that Google is almost obsessively serious about the responsibility of this enormous enterprise and do appear to be treating it with equal respect.   So there is no question that they are seeking out keen minds to challenge them on aspects they may have overlooked.  This position is extremely commendable.That said, I would challenge the reader of this post to pick out the key points below and take note, firstly if any of the components of the question were addressed, if so, to what extent and did he indicate in any way that he was cognizant of the existential impotence of the question put to him.  I see no evidence that he did.  ..."one of the things we discussed this morning was the difference between information and wisdom.  Google has a mission to organize the worlds information and I think ... if you think about the hierarchy there is signal, data, information and knowledge, and at and at the very top of the pyramid is wisdom.  And I wondered if you could comment a little bit on what you understand to be the difference between information and wisdom"...

author: @MrAndrew535

author: @taisa8776
processed_text: mehmet izci Hello! I don't know Brian Tracy, but what I have lived after being touched by Eckhart's teachings is this: you can have plans, you can set your goals and objectives, but you always have to go back to the Now. For an example: It's 6:30 PM and I just got home after work. I set up this time, in my schedule, to plan on the postgraduate course I wanna do. I'm at the stage of researching for one, so I go to the internet and check some universities's websites to see courses... by 7 PM I have to start doing dinner. It's 7 PM now and I haven't finished doing all the research I wanted, so I set up another time to do it, tomorrow. And now, as it is 7 PM, I go to the kitchen and start doing dinner: I take the vegetables from the refrigerator to prepare a salad, and as I do that, I'm REALLY doing that: I'm paying full attention at opening the fridge, looking for the vegetables, taking them, feeling their texture... in all these little actions, my attention is on what I'm doing NOW. I'm not thinking (while I do these things) "oh, tomorrow I'm looking at this or that university... but maybe it's too expansive... but I guess will be a good course..." I'm not thinking at all. I'm just there, doing dinner, maybe I can say I'm doing dinner and fully observing I'm doing dinner. This is being in the Now, and you can apply it to any situation in your life.So when it's time to plan, you plan. When it's time to sleep, you sleep. You do at the time whatever you have to do in the time, and that time is always Now.No matter what you set up as goal, every goal is made of smaller steps... As, in the example, to do a postgraduate course you must research where to do, compare different universities, then compare financial investments, see how to finance that, then decide for the course, then apply... etc. The key is to focus in every step as they happen, when they happen in the Now.I don't know if this helps you, hope it can =)

author: @AdelinGasana
processed_text: We see the same predictive story over and over again. Every cycle follows a similar pattern. It begins when growth picks up and companies invest in new capacity to meet perceived future needs. Production costs tend to escalate at this stage, as do asset prices, especially for equities and property, driven up in part by speculators. Inexpensive credit encourages businesses to commit to large, capital-intensive factories and offices. At this critical point, demand and current output both begin to slow, even as consumption continues to accelerate. A lack of savings spurs an increase in personal and commercial borrowing. To satisfy domestic demand, companies start to import more and export less, a trend that soon results in a balance-of-payments deficit. The economy is now officially out of kilter, freighted by over-investing, over-consumption, over-borrowing, and over-lending. Here beings the slide into recession. Prices are pushed higher by the use of less efficient means of production, by the growth in the money supply and by speculation. Tighter and much more expensive credit raises the cost of outstanding debt. Asset values, inflating in the upswing, are punctured. Borrowers can no longer make their payments, and the collateral available for new loans is restricted. Incomes, investment and consumption all fall off. Companies and entrepreneurs flounder or go bankrupt; unemployment rates rise. As confidence evaporates, borrowing and spending dry up. Long-term capital investments made in better days now come on line, increasing supply and depressing prices just as demand is slackening. Companies and individuals are forced to sell off assets at a loss, deepening the crisis, but many potential buyers wait for the market to hit bottom before purchasing, further delaying recovery. Me and you can guess what the next bubble will burst. Last time it was the housing bubble next will either be the student loan bubble or the healthcare cost bubble. Too many cycles of inconsistency and fragility like this will demand people and governments to make a paradigm shift on a new economic system away from the preceding one. Hence, post-capitalism...which is not a planned movement per se but more a gradual, natural move toward fundamental market principles of collective arrangement of labor, cohesive economic practices limiting turbulence, utilizing and expounding on abundant resources for all sectors of the economy, etc.

author: @SumeaBizarro
processed_text: I personally, completely disagree with "I get to say what it means" because "art is subjective" - Movies are a art form that can be rigid or open. Much like all art really. If the creator has made it very definitive your subjective opinion is not a quality of that artwork, it is projection of your views on the artwork. When creator tells straight "I have a clear idea what was real and what was not" - one going "but the film is so open so I get to make interpretations anyway right?" only within the limits of the author's words. It is very pompous to say you are higher than the creator when telling a meaning of art. That is not to say, many things said ring true, but there is also very pompous attitude dismissing the CREATOR HIMSELF. If anything he says contradicts you, you might want to go and seek other explanations. According to this video's "quote" what he said was open anyway, though I am sure he meant that certain parts are real.Other explanation would be, that there is reality, but it is made for viewer to question the "reality" of that world, and realizing it is not real at all.Maybe it is actually meta of Nolan's dream, shared with all the viewers. That would mean in the film's world, the first layer is real to the film, but unreal, because it ultimately is, which is the one nice point made in this talk.Overall it is a good talk, and raises good questions. But what I personally dislike, is for the consumer of art to be pompous enough to trample on any intentions the creator had, if he had set in stone, in his own words certain things about his work that he says are as they are.In video games, Silent Hill is one series trampled by many, many fan interpretations of things that happen during the plot of four first games. After this, the original team was disbanded completely and moved on to other projects, but because of franchise recognition, konami hired numerous, smaller teams to make more games for the series, which projected some fan interpretations, and even interpretations of the movie maker Gantz who made the movie adaptions, which also were filled with subjective, but ultimately false interpretations of the first game. This franchise now consists of far more works that are worse than the core beginning of three games since the fan interpretations under false pretense of "it is all vague anyway so I get to say what I think is the fact", until the point it was projected by the new makers who frankly had only fan interpretations to work with, since they did not want to invest time to take the games as they are, and work with that.

author: @thatintroguy1
processed_text: Why does he assume the dream level remains intact when everyone wakes? If the three dream levels collapse after everyone wakes, this leaves only two levels: Limbo (Cobb & Saito) and Reality (everyone else). When Saito kills himself he can't leave limbo while he is still sedated so he re-enters Limbo. The same happens to Cobb, but Limbo is now created from Saito's subconscious, including his being an old man. When the sedation finally wears off, Cobb and Saito leave Limbo and they go up one level to Reality.

author: @zadeh79
processed_text: Mr. Kahneman,. We don't need the just power to analyze information that is in front of us.   We need to power to build ideas when and where they are least expected.  Yes some of this building requires analysis, but first there are components of thought that allow us to make novel connections between the sea of distant elements.  The cult of the analytic (including Kahneman, have created a society where creativity has fallen behind.  Here is a quote regarding JOhn Von Neumann, "Two bicyclists start twenty miles apart and head toward each other, each going at a steady rate of 10 mph. At the same time a fly that travels at a steady 15 mph starts from the front wheel of the southbound bicycle and flies to the front wheel of the northbound one, then turns around and flies to the front wheel of the southbound one again, and continues in this manner till he is crushed between the two front wheels. Question: what total distance did the fly cover? The slow way to find the answer is to calculate what distance the fly covers on the first, northbound, leg of the trip, then on the second, southbound, leg, then on the third, etc., etc., and, finally, to sum the infinite series so obtained. The quick way is to observe that the bicycles meet exactly one hour after their start, so that the fly had just an hour for his travels; the answer must therefore be 15 miles. When the question was put to von Neumann, he solved it in an instant, and thereby disappointed the questioner: "Oh, you must have heard the trick before!" "What trick?" asked von Neumann, "All I did was sum the geometric series."      It's clear then that certain solutions are best developed with less conscious deliberation, rather the ability to automatically attract distant ideas into some novel permutation, and then upon a slight moment of reflection, realize there is something useful there.   As Einstein said, "The intuitive mind is a sacred gift and the rational mind is a faithful servant we have created a society that honors the servant and has forgotten the gift".

author: @danielgiegerz1251
processed_text: There aren't really two separate thinking 'Systems' in the brain. Only different processes , that work together to build relationships.  This making of this dichotomy is an aversion of the notion that reasoning and creativity is more than just IQ ('system 2') processes, but rather requires and experimental tinkering that can only come from functions attributed to 'System 1'.   But the system we live in, especially academia, completely ignores System 1 thinking, while System 2 takes the spotlight with standards tests and formal protocols.  Of course, the predictability of these protocols are limited.  Until we design theories of mind, that account for differences in real-time cognitive processing.   We owe genius to System 1, and commonality to System 2.

author: @DharmendraRaiMindMap
processed_text: About the start of his talk . Where does intuition make sense & where it does nt . I think its an easy answer . When you have time to think - think . Else use your intuition - as if that s a choice there :) . Would love to hear views on this

author: @zadeh79
processed_text: +Dharmendra Rai Intuition (as a sudden insight), works best when dealing with very complex systems, that cannot be analyzed with the limited scope of System 2 (limited by working/short-term memory +- 7 digits).  Intuition in large systems allows for arbitrary pieces of that system to be arrange into new models, which are then further analyzed for information.  The usual reason why most people are opposed to IQ tests, whether they know why or not, is because conventional reasoning theory suggests that reasoning involves merely analyzing sets, for example,  2, 8, 10, 40, however, these theories disregard the fact that novel sets can be constructed by the individual, for example, I can put together a sequence such as Box, Paper, Line, period,  and have an abstract idea in mind - but it is one that I completely created, even if my influence of selection, did involve similarities or factual information, the specific selection and arrangement of these items contains novelty, which IQ tests are blind to.  In very complex systems , like math or physics, the brain requires to pull ideas that are very distant and arrange them new ways - even when creating proofs and conjectures.   The pre-analytical processes, reflect essentially, the experimental capacity of the mind.  The great thought experiments of history are based on empirical connection of ideas; Galelios free fall, the Fizeau experiment, Einsteins relativity (Einstein a big believer of intuition). There is around 1000 years of philosophy that is dedicated to the power of observation and experimental thought (several hundred dedicated to a priori), yet reasoning theory has nothing to say about this.

author: @zadeh79
processed_text: +Dharmendra Rai Maybe I made it sound like System 1 only deals with complexity, it doesn't.  System 1 role in complexity, is that it allows one to select/create a novel arrangement of information,  when dealing with complex empirical systems (math/physics/chemistry/ect).  In this sense, System 1 deals with meta-compexity.  However, after information has been drawn together, system 2 takes over and can deal with micro-complexity.

author: @fergoesdayton
processed_text: Coneman and analytic proponents are bullshit.  He presents intuition as kind of a tool that is limited to  handling basic, reflexive operations, and seems to emphasize his claim that it is highly faulty.   But that is clearly false.  'System 1'   handles complexity some orders of magnitude greater than 'System 2', which is severely limited by Working memory capacity. System 1, type thinking is involved in parallel processing, selecting and creating sets/models (bringing ideas together).   System 2 , is involved in analyzing these models. Most Western philosophers of mind have praised intuition; Einstein and Poincare., but the contemporary Western Psychology is biased against it. We are not the author of intuitive thinking?! What crap!  Intuitive thinking is what allows us to relate distant ideas.  How does conehman think he chose the random numbers and operator, 24 * 17. He selected and ordered the elements, and created a relationship.  System 2 thinking has been long over-rated.

author: @lowereastsideastrologist7769
processed_text: fergoesdayton Exactly.  Though there really aren't 2 systems, but 2 components.   Intuitive thinking fast (usually), but definitely deals with complexity better.  'Intuition' is responsible for ordering and selecting ideas based on structural overlap (associative memory), injecting elements into a problem, creating ordered sets of information, and also responsible for dealing with complex processing and parallel integration of ideas.  Large problems don't fit in 'system 2', because it is limited to 7/ +- 2  bits of information.  Therefore, in contrast to Khaneman (Conman ..lol) complexity is dealt with best by System 1.  System 2 then analyzes results.  Intuition is important, because we never know when or where the insight to a complex problem will show up, so taking our time and trying really hard (System 2) is usually fruitless. We need to rely on evolutionary and adaptive heuristics (see gerd gigerenzer).  It's no wonder why Einstein valued intuition so much.  Yes, and even before Khaneman solved  24 * 17, intuition allowed him to pre-consciously select and order the number and operator.  As intutiion is allowing me to type these words without consciously selecting and ordering each word.   Khaneman is a fraud, and a gullible  and entitle-minded public, support him, because they would rather believe that great ideas are the product of some 'lazy' system 2 process then some underlying heuristic abilities that allow for the production of some novel permutations.P.S   I like your video on IQ test bias.

processed_text: Mindfulness is great, if you don't have a 3 year old that is running from room to room while you are trying to get ready for work and get to the bank, drop off the rent check and figure out how you are going to ask for that raise.  You'll convince me that this is a viable way to live when more tha Monks, Nuns, and Yuppie Dinks are able to practice it. author: @SavedbytheSaviour21
processed_text: I have a 1 year old and I practice mindfulness. Mindfulness is really about being mindful about the present moment. Practice being present while your child is running around and you are doing your daily duties. Don't be mindful of your thoughts but what's going on in the present moment without judgement - only observation. If nothing else, mindfulness starts with one breath. Just focus on one breath a day.

author: @michalchik
processed_text: Jefferson Steelflex and Andrew SenesacI appreciate you comments, and I am pretty sure I understood them even before you made them.My point is that often life places demands on you that requires a mind that is not just in the present, but that is anticipating the future and keeping track of several things.Sure you can be mindful while you are playing with a child, but not when you are making sure your child is safe, making breakfast, getting yourself ready for work, and planning your day.We live in a world where concentrating on just one thing at a time, in the present is not usually a viable option. The pace of life and rate of change in a Tibetan monastery leaves a lot of time to devotion to single task in the present moment. We live in a world where planning and anticipating about upcoming events while we are aware of our surroundings and engaged in  completing a task is that does not require full concentration such as cleaning or walking. Mindfulness is a luxury of a life with a slow pace, day to day sameness, and not many responsibilities. Most people don't have that option or even desire it.

author: @SavedbytheSaviour21
processed_text: Yeah, I totally understand what you mean by having a crazy day-to-day life full of responsibilities. I was much the same a few months back. Two jobs, a kid and a wife and all that comes with it kept me on my toes around the clock. Up until recently I was experiencing almost daily panic attacks. I had SO much I had to think about.I am not one to say you can be mindful every second of every day. But what Thich Nhat Hanh is getting at is for us - the lay people. We need a practical application to our daily lives which is why being mindful for even a minute or two a day is great. It breaks the train wreck of constant thinking, pondering, worrying, etc. And what I have found so far is even a little mindfulness everyday can really go a long way. Thanks for your reply and I hope all goes well.

author: @michalchik
processed_text: Andrew Senesac  Fair enough, I will grant that most people have time they could live in a mindful way, and in fact I think I do that myself. I just feel a bit pushed around by people saying, we should all live in the moment. No most of us can't live in the moment anymore than most of us can't live in Hawaii. We can only afford to vacation there.

author: @novusvoss
processed_text: michalchik The ironic story here is, that the very practice you think is unfit for a busy lifestyle, will be the one that benefits you most.In exactly the situations you mention, where you have to manage multiple tasks in a short timespan, being able to calm your mind and ground yourself will give you so much more control over yourself. It reduces stress, improves confidence and so on. I think you misunderstand this practice as taking break, but it's literally just a few seconds of letting your mind rest and getting back with full swing.It is very true that monks in a monestary have a much easier setting to practice these mental exercises than you, but they attempt to actually master them. You on the other hand only need to be a novice at this practice to see it benefit your life.Plus, there are multiple studies that prove that the human brain is incapable of proper multitasking. Multitasking just means doing many things in a bad way, when really our brain is designed to focus on one task at a time. Mindfullness helps a great deal with it.I know what you're thinking, "I don't have the luxury/time to work like that." And tho I understand, you'd be surprised how much time you save when you bring your full attention to finish one thing at a time. So please give it a (real) try. ;)

author: @flashoflight8160
processed_text: When results from drug trials are not hidden by the drug companies anymore (45% of the total number of drug studies), I'll trust evidence based medicine and conventional medicine. That's why sites like SBM are not convincing to many patients, including myself despite the huge wall of well written text. If you cherrypick the drug studies to get FDA approval, you're no more trustworthy than functional medicine. I don't completely trust the oncologists pushing expensive chemo drugs for big pharma just like I don't trust FM docs who push supplements. I'm not going to turn down 80% survival with chemo vs. 50% with no chemo, but my trust in science is gone. Money corrupts no matter who it is. In the end, we're down to anecdotes from real patients (not supplement pushers) because the scientific evidence is incomplete thanks to big pharma. There are a lot of anecdotes and positive n=1 results in my family with FM, so we will take the easy and cheap parts of FM (eg. gluten free diet).
