author: @Cyrribrae
processed_text: Bradley Jones What? Show me what tech we already have that does hand tracking to this degree of fidelity? The tracking tech that I know of can barely distinguish a few basic finger/hand poses.

author: @BradleyJones123
processed_text: Cyrribrae The video says nothing about fidelity other than a vague reference at the end of the video. As such, the types of things discussed in this video are similar to what has been discussed with Kinect, Real Sense, and Leap Motion as well as what has been seen with demos of HoloLens.  It could be that the disconnect is that the video doesn't clearly state that the focus here is in a higher resolution and thus much better tracking down to a more specific finger gesture rather than more of a hand gesture.As a note: I'm not bashing the technology - I'm obviously interested as I watched the video and took the time to comment. My comment was more a reference to what was stated in the video. Touching on how Handpose is unique didn't come across clearly in the video, which I think is obvious from the comments.

author: @Cyrribrae
processed_text: Sorry, I mean looking at the video itself you can tell that the tech here is more advanced than we've publicly seen elsewhere.It's a fair criticism that the video wasn't clear about what this can do, though there is a longer and better tech demo somewhere. But either way, I don't believe any of the major VR companies, besides Leap Motion (kinda? maybe?), are investing a ton in articulated hand tracking - because it's hard. Hololens and Kinect can only recognize a few specific hand poses, so far. That's not to say that this tech is definitely actually that much better, but it seems like it to me. And yea, this video is underwhelming, the tech demo is much more impressive.

author: @BradleyJones123
processed_text: Cyrribrae  If Handpose is used in HoloLens, then it will be doing a much better job than what we've seen in Kinect and the other tech to date. In the hands-on demo for HoloLens, they show a couple of hand gestures for controlling, selecting and such. It will also be interesting to see how Oculus Touch does with gesture recognition as well. Granted, that is a different approach since it requires holding a device. Overall, the tech is getting better and it seems what is falling behind is the software that has been developed. When the software catches up and the application of the hardware and software hit the mainstream market, then (I believe) Minority Report will start to look tame.

author: @2pimpinout
processed_text: I think that rather than working around traffic issues, we should tackle the cause of traffic.1) If you look at the cars in the traffic jams, there is usually one driver per car. Imagine if we grabbed four drivers from four different cars and put them into one car. That would now prevent those three cars from being the source of the traffic jam. We need to figure out a reward system that will reward drivers who will do carpool and companies that will schedule employees at similar time, so they can carpool.2) The speed limit of freeways is also another issue. When we have a freeway that has the speed limit of 55, as soon as congestion starts occurring, the speed starts dropping down to 45,35,25 in one hour, for instance. Now, if the speed limit was 75, if because of the congestion, the speed starts dropping down, within an hour, it might only drop down to 65, 55, 45 - which is waaayyy better than going 25mph.3) Have cities approve the self driving cars. Humans are very accident prone and having self driving cars have much less accidents, close to none. A lot of times, when an accident occurs, two things happenFirst, the drivers don't move out of the way, and cars have to switch lanes, causing major congestion.Second, the drivers will move out of the way. However, the spectators will slow down just to see the accident. That causes a domino effect, which causes a traffic jam miles behind.

author: @StephenPaulKing

author: @StephenPaulKing
processed_text: Richard Gecko Good one.Some reasoning can not be expressed in sequences of symbols. The actions of transformations of topological spaces is a good example. Tell me that there is a "best way" to describe the transformation of a complicated knot that is tangled in one way into the same knot tangled in a different way. Sequences, and sequences of symbols, are great at describing and representing trajectories of single particles moving in a space, but really suck at talking about the global properties of that space.    Might there exist "spatial logics" that can do this thing that sequential logics fail at? Yes, for example:http://arxiv.org/abs/1103.6007

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 11:30 Children have their agency usurped by adults11:37 They have their understanding of situations undermined by shifting technologies, changing affordances. Boyd uses the example of the privacy settings changing suddenly. KG: We all agree to the new terms and conditions that apply when we download or update an app or continue to use FB through it's various changes.11:47 "All of a sudden new people are in the environment" and kids are trying to deal with how that changes the situation.11:50 Young people are struggling to assert their control, more or less, that makes sense for their needs.11:57 12:45 Shift in technical affordances: BEFORE ONLINE private by default, public by effort. AFTER ONLINE: public by default, public by effort, 14:04 They are not trying to BE public. Young people are not trying to BE SEENby all people across all space and all time, but rather they are trying to find A public they can participate in. 14:20 In the U.S., young people have few opportunities to engage with their peers, where young people can just hang out. Social media is the path for finding A public.  Doesn't meant they are trying to BE public.14:45 Young people don't understand why adults don't respect their boundaries.15:08 Strategies for privacy

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 10:22 Paraphrasing boyd: On one hand we know our content is publicly accessible. "Anybody could look at it." But we have limits in our attitudes, values and norms about who should be accessing, reading or viewing our content online that is based on offline standards from meatspaces or F2F offline spaces and interactions. Parents entering your room as a teenager is off limits. Parents are "out of place" in the privacy of your room. 10:31 "Privacy isn't about whether or not [your] content is accessible, but what the norms are that govern that access."10:45 Flickr photo: Close-up of white, female child with glittered butterfly mask held up to her face. 10:46 Privacy is not about hiding or excluding oneself rather it's about having a sense of control.10:55 Not control over data but 1) your ability to define your reality (agency in social settings, power in situations) and 2) to have enough critical awareness or social/political skill within that situation to use one's agency to negotiate power within the setting/situation with other people.11:20 The combination of agency and the ability to understand, interpret and manuever the rules and norms of the situation (situational negotiation of identity in the context of symbolic interactionism -- sociological and anthropological concepts) are extraordinarily hard in an online environment.

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 9:15 danah boyd; "We have a public understanding that certain spaces are more or less public. The home is relatively private, though any body who has children knows it's not as private as your want it to be. 9:28 "We have certain ideas about certain spaces being very public, say for example, the park.9:34 And yet at times we say very private things in very public places and vice versa.9:39 In an online environment those boundaries get a lot more blurred. And it's that blurring where we start to see privacy getting contested and confused."

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 9:10 Third key dynamic is blurring of what we normally think of as public and private. Slide: "Public/Private blurring: without control over context, public and private become meaningless binaries, are scaled in new ways, and are difficult to maintain as distinct" in our mental maps of reality. Our norms and values often remain the same while the contexts have blurred, collapsed and shifted from our local history, culture and meaning systems. We usually do not notice until the collision causes a breakdown in our real lives (publicity gets you in trouble OR you ignore the reactions of others from your publicity--become indifferent and perhaps naive relative to the implications for your future self).

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 9:03 Interesting how I, perhaps others are similar, do not intuitively situate privacy and the word publicity as opposites. Publicity is for celebrities or public entities or figures and individual citizens and I would think youth may not assume what they do is "publicity". And it if is, it's "publicity" for what? For attention, money--monetized YouTube channels, social capital? It's also publicity for your future self. That they cannot fully fathom without the long-term capacities of a fully developed brain. And even adults--myself included--do not always "plan" well or anticipate the future moment much less the future future very well--5, 10, 20 or 50 years from now. What's most present is the past and the present present. The now.

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 8:40 "How do you understand what a given context is? A context is driven by your understanding of the space, the environment of what's going on -- what the rules and norms are for that space" and for the particular people in that space. You develop ways of relating to people and things based on context. For people of color and women, that must include biology -- your perceived skin color, race, sex, age, gender, sexuality, class, religion, ability/disability, etc. Ecological studies of context can easily overlook these aspects of identity that already have meanings collapsed and otherwise in networked settings.

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 9:00 Context collision is a really hard thing to navigate.Esp. for youth and even more so for girls and girls of color who are not digital media savvy or literate, who are experimenting with the presentation of their self on YouTube for instance for the first time or first period in their adolescence. They do it immediately without any consciousness of the pervasive persistence and the timeless searchability of the media they upload on social media sites as digital video.

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 8:39 how do you understand what a given context is? Context is driven by your understanding of the space, what's going on relative to rules and norms of the space AND the people, how you relate to particular people (KG: which I would add includes your "self". You are in that moment constructing your relationship to your self as well as to particular generalized others online and off].

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 8:05 Another key dynamic is collapsed contexts. The norms in the room where danah is speaking. You would violate the context if you got up and started dancing.8:34 Slide: Collapsed contexts defined -- "lack of spatial, social and temporal boundaries makes it difficult to maintain distinct social contexts". KG: I'd add here it makes it difficult to determine the discourse the words used to exchange meaning and value and determine to whom you are vs. who you want to exchange value with online including your future self. This is why, as danah boyd's book title suggests, it's complicated. It's further complicated for subjects online that are both racialized and sexualized in stigmatizing ways to negotiate their digital self-presentation in these collapsed contexts where they may be seen by no one or tens, hundreds of thousands of networked individual or tens, hundreds or thousands of social groups of youth clustering around a mobile device who have their own diverse and collapsing shared norms and values that may be globalizing stereotypes of "othered" youth while granting them social capital--making them for instance FB or Instagram famous.

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 6:30 Invisible audiences introduced7:00 There is also a camera pointed at me and I don't know who is behind the camera. If I am being listened to in 2012 or 2013. 7:26 Young people have to navigate invisible audiences as a process of participation everyday. They try to imagine who their audience is7:45 Your "friends list" on social media is an articulation of who you WANT the audience to be. Who you imagine the audience to be and who you think you are speaking to.7:51 How do you navigate all of these invisible audiences7:54 Many adults like to play ostrich (stick their head in the sand) and pretend those audiences don't exist.8:00 Young people are hoping that these audiences might pay attention to them in a positive way. It's always a challenge.

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 23:50 this steganography has been a tactic of what danah calls "minority" populations that I would prefer to call "oppressed" populations and groups as she said "forever". Music has been a key code for steganography in black culture.

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 21;06 The mom post and Carmen after a breakup. Negotiates communicating to friends without triggering her mother. Song lyrics from Monty Python reference Always look on the Bright Side of Life. She puts up song lyrics and mom things she's having a great day and her friends call her to provide support. Achieving privacy in a public environment. 22:25 danah explains teens' practice of "social stegonography". See this link for historical context of the term steganography: http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/05/how-to-stash-secret-messages-in-tweets-using-point-and-click-steganography/

author: @kyraocity
processed_text: 15:18 - 17:50 A young person Hunter lives in DC; dealing with context collapse in his online interactions. Friends, peers, and sister represent conflicting worlds as he interacts online.  I am very curious how social media agencies and experts lack of racial markers of social identity like "young black person" is not eliminating the biases that exist in our world that shape the context collapses of online interactions.
